insey & Company people]]\n[[Category:Arkansas lawyers]]\n[[Category:Arkansas Republicans]]\n[[Category:Federalist Society members]]\n[[Category:Harvard Crimson alumni]]\n[[Category:Harvard Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from Arkansas]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Arkansas]]\n[[Category:People from Dardanelle, Arkansas]]\n[[Category:Republican Party United States senators]]\n[[Category:Tea Party movement activists]]\n[[Category:United States Army officers]]\n[[Category:United States Army Rangers]]\n[[Category:United States senators from Arkansas]]\n[[Category:Writers from Arkansas]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|United States Senator from Arkansas}}\n{{Use American English|date=August 2017}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2016}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name                = Tom Cotton\n| image               = Tom Cotton official Senate photo.jpg\n| jr/sr               = United States Senator\n| state               = [[Arkansas]]\n| alongside           = [[John Boozman]]\n| term_start          = January 3, 2015\n| term_end            = \n| predecessor         = [[Mark Pryor]]\n| successor           = \n| state1              = [[Arkansas]]\n| district1           = {{ushr|AR|4|4th}}\n| term_start1         = January 3, 2013\n| term_end1           = January 3, 2015\n| predecessor1        = [[Mike Ross (politician)|Mike Ross]]\n| successor1          = [[Bruce Westerman]]\n| birth_name          = Thomas Bryant Cotton\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date and age|1977|05|13}}\n| birth_place         = [[Dardanelle, Arkansas]], U.S.\n| death_date          = \n| party               = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n| spouse              = {{marriage|Anna Peckham|March 15, 2014}}\n| children            = 2\n| education           = [[Harvard University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|AB]], [[Juris Doctor|JD]])\n| website             = {{url|https://cotton.senate.gov|Senate website}}\n| allegiance          = {{flag|United States}}\n| branch              = {{army|United States}}\n| serviceyears        = {{ublist|2005\u20132009 (active)|2009\u20132013 (reserve)}} <!-- EDITORS NOTE: Please do not change service years without prior consensus, see [[Talk:Tom Cotton]]. -->\n| rank                = [[File:Army-USA-OF-02.svg|38px]] [[Captain (United States O-3)|Captain]]\n| unit                = {{ublist|[[506th Infantry Regiment (United States)|506th Infantry Regiment]], [[101st Airborne Division]]|[[3rd U.S. Infantry Regiment (The Old Guard)|3d Infantry Regiment]]}} <!-- EDITORS NOTE: Please do not change unit without prior consensus, see [[Talk:Tom Cotton]]. -->\n| battles             = [[War on Terror|War on Terrorism]]<br /> <!-- EDITORS NOTE: Please do not change battles/wars without prior consensus, see [[Talk:Tom Cotton]]. -->\n{{bulleted list|[[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|Afghanistan Campaign]]|[[Iraq War|Iraq Campaign]]}} <!-- EDITORS NOTE: Please do not change military campaigns without prior consensus, see [[Talk:Tom Cotton]]. -->\n| mawards             = {{ublist|[[File:Bronze Star ribbon.svg|border|23px]] [[Bronze Star Medal]]|[[File:Combat Infantry Badge.svg|23px]] [[Combat Infantryman Badge]]|[[File:Ranger Tab.svg|23px]] [[Ranger Tab]]}} <!-- EDITORS NOTE: Please do not change military awards without prior consensus, see [[Talk:Tom Cotton]]. -->\n}}\n{{Conservatism in the United States}}\n'''Thomas Bryant Cotton''' (born May 13, 1977) is an American attorney, military veteran, and politician serving as the [[Seniority in the United States Senate|junior]] [[United States Senate|United States senator]] for [[Arkansas]] since January 3, 2015. He is a member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]].\nIn 2005, he commissioned in the U.S. Army, where he rose to the rank of captain. Cotton's military background includes service in Afghanistan and deployment to Iraq during Operation Iraqi Freedom; he is a [[Bronze Star Medal|Bronze Star]] recipient.\nCotton served in the [[United States House of Representatives]] from 2013 to 2015. He was elected to the U.S. Senate at age 37 in [[2014 United States Senate election in Arkansas|2014]], defeating two-term [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] incumbent [[Mark Pryor]].\n\n==Early life, education, and military career (1977\u20132013)==\n===Formative years and education===\nTom Cotton was born on May 13, 1977 in [[Dardanelle, Arkansas]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=C001095 |work= Biographical Directory of the United States Congress |title= Tom Cotton |accessdate= November 5, 2018}}</ref> Cotton's father, Thomas Leonard \"Len\" Cotton, was a district supervisor in the Arkansas Health Department, and his mother, Avis (n\u00e9e Bryant) Cotton, was a schoolteacher who later became principal of their district's middle school.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.arktimes.com/arkansas/tom-cotton-wouldnt-be-anywhere-without-government-dollars/Content?oid=3479339|title=Tom Cotton wouldn't be anywhere without government dollars|first=Gene|last=Lyons|work=[[Arkansas Times]]|date=October 9, 2014}}</ref> Cotton's family had lived in rural Arkansas for seven generations, and he grew up on his family's cattle farm.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.swtimes.com/sections/news/politics/new-arkansas-rep-cotton-draws-spotlight-113th-congress-sworn.html|title=New Arkansas Rep. Cotton Draws Spotlight; 113th Congress Sworn In|work=[[Times Record News]]|date=January 4, 2013}}</ref><ref name=superstar>{{cite news|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/features/archive/2014/09/the-making-of-a-conservative-superstar/380307|title=The Making of a Conservative Superstar|first=Molly|last=Ball|work=[[The Atlantic]]|date=September 17, 2014}}</ref> He attended [[Dardanelle High School]] where he played on the local and regional basketball teams; standing {{height|ft=6|in=5}} tall, he was usually required to play [[Center (basketball)|center]].<ref name=\"superstar\" /><ref name=gitom>{{cite news|url=http://www.nationalreview.com/article/279170/gi-tom-brian-bolduc|title=G.I. Tom|first=Brian|last=Bolduc|work=[[National Review]]|date=October 7, 2011}}</ref>\n\nWhile in high school, Cotton developed an intense desire to attend [[Harvard College]], and worked intently on his studies toward that goal.<ref name=\"superstar\" /> He was accepted to Harvard after graduating from high school in 1995, and majored in government. At Harvard, Cotton was a member of the editorial board of ''[[The Harvard Crimson]]'', often dissenting from the liberal majority.<ref name=gitom/> In articles, Cotton addressed what he saw as \"[[Sacred cow (idiom)|sacred cows]]\" such as [[affirmative action]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usnews.com/news/articles/2015/04/16/tom-cotton-takes-on-the-world|title=Tom Cotton Takes On the World|first=Gabrielle|last=Levy|work=[[U.S. News & World Report]]|date=April 16, 2015}}</ref> He graduated with an [[Bachelor of Arts|A.B.]] ''[[Latin honors#types|magna cum laude]]'' in 1998 after only three years of study, having written his senior thesis on ''[[The Federalist Papers]]''.<ref name=\"superstar\" />\n\nAfter graduating from Harvard, Cotton was accepted into a master's degree program at [[Claremont Graduate University]]. He left in 1999, saying that he found academic life \"too sedentary\", and instead enrolled at [[Harvard Law School]].<ref name=superstar/> Cotton graduated from Harvard Law School with a [[Juris Doctor|J.D.]] degree in 2002.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=C001095|title=COTTON, Tom|publisher=[[United States Congress]]}}</ref>\n\nAfter finishing law school in 2002, he served for a year as a clerk for Judge [[Jerry Edwin Smith]] at the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Fifth Circuit]]. He then entered the [[practice of law]], working at [[Gibson, Dunn & Crutcher]] for a few months to start paying off his [[student loans]], and later at the law firm of [[Charles J. Cooper]] & Kirk from 2003 to 2004.<ref name=trumpism>{{cite news|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2017/11/13/is-tom-cotton-the-future-of-trumpism|title=Is Tom Cotton the Future of Trumpism?|first=Jeffrey|last=Toobin|work=[[The New Yorker]]|date=November 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Military service===\nOn January 11, 2005, Cotton commissioned in the [[U.S. Army]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/tom-cotton/story?id=40290944|title=Tom Cotton: Everything You Need to Know|first=ALI|last=ROGIN|work=[[ABC News]]|date=July 18, 2016}}</ref> Cotton declined offers to serve in the [[Judge Advocate General's Corps, United States Army|Army J.A.G. Corps]] and instead volunteered for the infantry. Cotton had resolved to serve as an Army infantryman in his third year of law school while watching live news coverage of the [[September 11 attacks]], and had begun a regimen of physical exercise and studying military history.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Stern |first1=Seth |title=For Freshman Senator Tom Cotton, politics and patriotism are nothing new |url=https://today.law.harvard.edu/politics-and-service/ |website=Harvard Law Today |accessdate=7 September 2018}}</ref> In March 2005, he entered [[Officer Candidate School (U.S. Army)|Officer Candidate School]], and in June 2005 was commissioned a [[Second Lieutenant#United States|second lieutenant]] of infantry.<ref name=DefensePAC>{{cite press release|title=NATIONAL DEFENSE PAC today announces with extreme pride its endorsement of Congressman Thomas Cotton|url=http://nationaldefensepac.org/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/Tom_Cotton_Endorsement.pdf|publisher=National Defense PAC|date=October 6, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2006, Cotton was deployed to [[Baghdad]] as part of [[Operation Iraqi Freedom]] as a platoon leader with the [[101st Airborne Division]]. In [[Iraq]], he led a 41-man [[air assault]] infantry platoon in the [[506th Infantry Regiment]], and planned and performed daily combat patrols.<ref name=DefensePAC/> In December 2006, Cotton was promoted to [[First Lieutenant#United States|first lieutenant]]. He was assigned as a platoon leader for the [[3rd U.S. Infantry Regiment (The Old Guard)]] at [[Joint Base Myer\u2013Henderson Hall|Fort Myer]], Virginia.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.philly.com/philly/opinion/commentary/20170601_Congress_must_support_Arlington_expansion.html|title=Congress must support Arlington expansion|first=Tom|last=Cotton|work=[[Philadelphia Media Network]]|date=May 31, 2017}}</ref> In October 2008, Cotton was deployed to eastern [[Afghanistan]]. He was assigned within the [[Train Advise Assist Command \u2013 East]] at its Gamberi [[forward operating base]] (FOB) in [[Laghman Province]] as the Operations Officer of a [[Provincial Reconstruction Team]], where he planned daily [[counter-insurgency]] and reconstruction operations.<ref name=DefensePAC/> His 11-month deployment ended on July 20, 2009 and he returned from Afghanistan.<ref name=DefensePAC/> \n\nIn July 2010, Cotton transferred to the [[United States Army Reserve]]. His military record shows his final discharge from the U.S. Army Reserve was in May 2013; he was awarded the [[Bronze Star Medal]] and earned a [[Ranger Tab]], [[Combat Infantryman Badge]], [[Parachutist Badge]], [[Air Assault Badge]], [[Afghanistan Campaign Medal]], and [[Iraq Campaign Medal]].<ref name=DefensePAC/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/dana-milbank-for-tom-cotton-a-military-record-is-no-magic-bullet/2014/05/12/7442cb7c-da1e-11e3-8009-71de85b9c527_story.html|title=Dana Milbank: For Tom Cotton, a military record is no magic bullet|first=Dana|last=Milbank|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=May 12, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Tom Cotton Army Service Record|url=https://www.muckrock.com/foi/united-states-of-america-10/tom-cotton-military-records-13249/#files|publisher=[[MuckRock]]}}</ref>\n\n====Call for the imprisonment of ''New York Times'' journalists====\nIn June 2006, while stationed in Iraq, Cotton gained international public attention after he wrote an open letter to the editor of ''[[The New York Times]]'', accusing three journalists of violating \"espionage laws\" by publishing an article detailing a Bush administration secret program monitoring terrorists' finances. ''The New York Times'' did not publish the letter, but it was published on ''[[Power Line]]'', a conservative blog that had been copied on the email.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.powerlineblog.com/archives/2012/10/a-fateful-letter-to-the-editor-of-the-times.php|last=Johnson|first=Scott|title=A FATEFUL LETTER TO THE EDITOR OF THE TIMES|publisher=[[Power Line]]|date=October 23, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Leibovich|first=Mark|title=Tom Cotton Is Not Mailing It In|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/04/05/magazine/tom-cotton-is-not-mailing-it-in.html|website=[[The New York Times Magazine]]|publisher=[[The New York Times]]|date=April 5, 2015}}</ref> In the letter, Cotton called for the journalists responsible for the newspaper article to be imprisoned for [[espionage]]. He asserted that the newspaper had \"gravely endangered the lives of my soldiers and all other soldiers and innocent Iraqis here.\" The article was widely circulated online and reprinted in full in several newspapers.<ref>{{cite web|last=Baumann|first=Nick|title=The GOP Candidate Who Wants Journos Jailed|url=https://www.motherjones.com/politics/2011/11/tom-cotton-arkansas-new-york-times|website=[[Mother Jones (magazine)|Mother Jones]]|date=November 10, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Political career (2013\u2013present)==\nShortly after Cotton's Afghanistan deployment ended, his former boss at the Claremont Institute introduced Cotton to [[Chris Chocola]], a former congressman and the president of [[Club for Growth]], an influential Republican [[political action committee]].<ref name=superstar/> An attempt was made to draft Cotton for the [[2010 United States Senate election in Arkansas]] to run against incumbent Democratic U.S. senator [[Blanche Lincoln]]. Cotton declined, believing he would be rushing a political candidacy.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/tom-cotton-mark-pryor-senate-2014-challenger-biography-2013-8|title=10 Things Everyone Should Know About Tom Cotton, The Arkansas Politician Who Should Scare The Hell Out Of Democrats|first=Brett|last=LoGiurato|publisher=[[Business Insider]]|date=August 12, 2013}}</ref> Following his active duty service, Cotton served in the Army Reserve and did sporadic consulting work for [[McKinsey & Company]],<ref name=superstar/><ref name=nordlinger>{{cite news|url=http://www.nationalreview.com/article/331200/tom-cotton-arkansas-part-ii-jay-nordlinger|title=Tom Cotton of Arkansas, Part II|first=Jay|last=Nordlinger|work=[[National Review]]|date=October 23, 2012}}</ref> before running for Congress in [[Arkansas' 4th congressional district]] following the retirement announcement of [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] incumbent [[Mike Ross (politician)|Mike Ross]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/ballot-box/house-races/173233-rep-mike-ross-to-announce-political-future|title=Rep. Mike Ross to retire|first=Cameron|last=Joseph|work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]|date=July 25, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.arktimes.com/ArkansasBlog/archives/2011/07/25/surprise-mike-ross-announcement-today|title=U.S. Rep. Mike Ross won't seek 2012 re-election|first=Max|last=Brantley|work=[[Arkansas Times]]|date=July 25, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===U.S. House of Representatives (2013-2015)===\n{{See also|2012 United States House of Representatives elections in Arkansas}}\n[[File:Debate 10.4.12 (8070720129).jpg|thumb|upright|Cotton participating in a 2012 congressional debate at [[Southern Arkansas University]]]]\nIn September 2011, Cotton faced criticism for an article that he wrote in ''The Harvard Crimson'' in 1998, in which he questioned the value of the Internet as a teaching tool in the classroom, referring to the internet as having \"too many temptations\" to be useful in schools and libraries. Cotton later stated that the internet had matured since he wrote the article in 1998.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.arktimes.com/ArkansasBlog/archives/2011/09/01/tom-cotton-learns-value-of-internet|title=Tom Cotton learns value of Internet|first=Max|last=Brantley|work=[[Arkansas Times]]| date=September 1, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://cei.org/blog/tom-cottons-last-minute-anti-gambling-bill|title=Tom Cotton's Last Minute Anti-Gambling Bill|first=Michelle|last=Minton|work=[[Competitive Enterprise Institute]]| date=September 26, 2016}}</ref>\n\nBeth Anne Rankin, the 2010 Republican nominee, and John David Cowart, who carried the backing of the Louisiana businessman and philanthropist [[Edgar Cason]], were the only other Republican candidates in the race after candidate Marcus Richmond dropped out in February 2012.<ref name=gitom/> In the primary on May 22, 2012, Cotton won the Republican nomination, with 57.6% of the vote; in second place was Beth Ann Rankin who received 37.1% of the vote.<ref name=arkansas2012>{{cite web|url=https://ballotpedia.org/Arkansas%27s_4th_Congressional_District_elections,_2012|title=Arkansas's 4th Congressional District elections, 2012|website=[[Ballotpedia]]}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Club for Growth]] endorsed Cotton.<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.clubforgrowth.org/press-release/club-for-growth-pac-endorses-tom-cotton-for-congress|title=CLUB FOR GROWTH PAC ENDORSES TOM COTTON FOR CONGRESS|publisher=[[Club for Growth]]|date=February 14, 2012}}</ref> Of the $2.2 million Cotton raised for that campaign, Club for Growth donors were responsible for $315,000 and were Cotton's largest supporters.<ref name=superstar/><ref name=nordlinger/> Cotton was also endorsed by Senator [[John McCain]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Miller|first=Joshua|title=Arkansas: Tom Cotton Gets John McCain Endorsement|url=http://www.rollcall.com/politics/arkansas-tom-cotton-gets-john-mccain-endorsement|work=[[Roll Call]]|date=May 3, 2012}}</ref> Cotton was supported by both the [[Tea Party movement]] and the Republican establishment.<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.teapartyexpress.org/4466/tea-party-express-endorses-tom-cotton-in-arkansas|title=Tea Party Express Endorses Tom Cotton in Arkansas|publisher=[[Tea Party Express]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/ballot-box/senate-races/314665-report-tom-cotton-will-run-for-senate-in-arkansas|title=Cotton's decision to run for Senate gives GOP 'rock star' candidate in Arkansas|first=Cameron|last=Joseph|work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]|date=July 31, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn the general election on November 6, Cotton defeated state senator [[Gene Jeffress]], 59.5% to 36.7%.<ref name=arkansas2012/> Cotton was the second Republican since [[Reconstruction Era of the United States]] to represent the 4th district. The first, [[Jay Dickey]], held it from 1993 to 2001 \u2014 during the presidency of [[Bill Clinton]], whose residence was in the district at the time.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2012/12/03/politics/freshman-office-search/index.html|title=Freshman's House office search foreshadows the legislator he might be|first=Dan|last=Merica|publisher=[[CNN]]|date=December 3, 2012}}</ref> On January 3, 2013, Cotton was sworn into the U.S. House of Representatives by [[United States Speaker of the House|Speaker]] [[John Boehner]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/tom-cotton-trump-cia-director-senator-bio-photos-2017-11|title=Meet Tom Cotton, the Arkansas senator with Trump's ear who graduated from Harvard in 3 years and might become the next head of the CIA|first=Michal|last=Kranz|publisher=[[Business Insider]]|date=November 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAs a freshman, Cotton was considered a rising star in the Republican Party. ''[[Politico (newspaper)|Politico]]'' named him \"most likely to succeed.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2013/01/freshman-yearbook-most-likely-to-085703|title=The freshman most likely to ________ |first=KATE|last=NOCERA|publisher=[[Politico]]|date=January 2, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/right-turn/wp/2012/12/05/tom-cotton-no-ordinary-freshman-congressman|title=Tom Cotton: No ordinary freshman congressman|first=Jennifer|last=Rubin|publisher=[[The Washington Post]]|date=December 5, 2012}}</ref> He quickly became a vocal opponent of the Obama administration's foreign and domestic policies. He voted for [[An Act to eliminate the 2013 statutory pay adjustment for Federal employees]], which prevented a 0.5% pay increase for all federal workers from taking effect in February 2013.<ref>{{cite web|title=HR 273 \u2013 Eliminates the 2013 Statutory Pay Adjustment for Federal Employees \u2013 Voting Record|url=https://votesmart.org/bill/votes/42596#.UjdQCD9-q1c|website=[[Project Vote Smart]]}}</ref> Cotton voted against the [[Federal Agriculture Reform and Risk Management Act of 2013|2013 Farm Bill]] over concerns about waste and fraud in [[Supplemental Nutrition Assistance Program]] voting later that month to strip funding from food stamps.<ref>{{cite news|last=Huey-Burns|first=Caitlin|title=Tom Cotton a Key House Voice on Immigration Reform|url=https://www.realclearpolitics.com/articles/2013/07/16/tom_cotton_a_key_house_voice_on_immigration_reform_119235.html|work=[[RealClearPolitics]]|date=July 16, 2013}}</ref> He also voted against the revised measure, the [[Agricultural Act of 2014]],<ref>{{cite web|title=House Floor Activities Legislative Day of January 29, 2014|url=http://clerk.house.gov/floorsummary/floor.aspx?day=20140129&today=20140212|website=House of Representatives}}</ref> which expanded crop insurance and a price floor for rice farmers.<ref>{{cite news|last=Nixon|first=Ron|title=Senate Passes Long-Stalled Farm Bill, With Clear Winners and Losers|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/02/05/us/politics/senate-passes-long-stalled-farm-bill.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=February 4, 2014}}{{subscription required}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://money.cnn.com/2014/02/04/news/economy/food-stamps-farm-bill/index.html|title=Senate passes farm bill|first=Jennifer|last=Liberto|publisher=[[CNNMoney]]|date=February 4, 2014}}</ref>\n\nCotton accused Obama of holding up a \"false choice\" between his framework deal on Iran's nuclear program and war. Cotton also seemed to underestimate what military action against Iran would entail,<ref name=\"npr\">{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/blogs/itsallpolitics/2015/04/08/398345234/tom-cotton-military-action-against-iran-would-only-take-several-days|title=Tom Cotton: Military Action Against Iran Would Take Only 'Several Days'|last=Montanaro|first=Domenico|website=[[NPR]]|date=April 8, 2015}}</ref> stating: \"the president is trying to make you think it would be 150,000 heavy mechanized troops on the ground in the Middle East again as we saw in Iraq. That's simply not the case.\" Drawing a comparison to President Bill Clinton's actions in 1998 during the [[Bombing of Iraq (1998)]], he elaborated: \"Several days' air and naval bombing against Iraq's weapons of mass destruction facilities for exactly the same kind of behavior. For interfering with weapons inspectors and for disobeying Security Council resolutions.\"<ref name=\"npr\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2015/04/tom-cotton-iran-targeted-attack-116768.html|title=Sen. Tom Cotton says U.S. could pursue targeted attack on Iran|author=Kendall Breitman|date=April 8, 2015|website=POLITICO}}</ref> On July 21, 2015, Cotton and [[Mike Pompeo]] claimed to have uncovered the existence of secret side agreements between Iran and the [[International Atomic Energy Agency]] (IAEA) on procedures for inspection and verification of Iran's nuclear activities under the [[Joint Comprehensive Plan of Action]] nuclear deal. Obama administration officials acknowledged the existence of agreements between Iran and the IAEA governing the inspection of sensitive military sites, but denied the characterization that they were \"secret side deals\", calling them standard practice in crafting arms-control pacts and arguing the administration had provided information about them to Congress.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://thehill.com/policy/international/249171-white-house-launches-counterattack-against-iran-side-deal-attacks|title=White House launches Iran side deals counterattack|first1=Jordan|last1=Fabian|first2=Kristina|last2=Wong|work=The Hill|date=July 26, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/john-kerry-iran-deal-iaea_us_55b14997e4b08f57d5d41c12|title=John Kerry's Confident The IAEA Can Handle Iran, But Congress Isn't Buying It|first=Jessica|last=Schulberg|work=[[The Huffington Post]]|date=December 19, 2016}}</ref>\n\n====Committee assignments====\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Financial Services]]'''\n** [[United States House Financial Services Subcommittee on Financial Institutions and Consumer Credit]]\n** [[United States House Financial Services Subcommittee on Monetary Policy and Trade]]\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Foreign Affairs]]'''\n** [[United States House Foreign Affairs Subcommittee on the Middle East and North Africa]]\n** [[United States House Foreign Affairs Subcommittee on Terrorism, Nonproliferation, and Trade]]\n\n===U.S. Senate (2015\u2013present)===\n[[File:Jon Kyl and Tom Cotton 28024309880 (cropped).jpg|thumb|Cotton and Senator [[Jon Kyl]] speaking at [[Hudson Institute]]]]\n[[File:U.S. Senator Tom Cotton and former Ambassador to the U.N. John Bolton speaking at the 2015 Conservative Political Action Conference (CPAC) in Maryland.jpg|thumb|Senator Cotton and former Ambassador to the U.N. [[John R. Bolton]] at the 2015 [[Conservative Political Action Conference]] (CPAC)]]\n[[File:U.S. Secretary of Defense Ash Carter and Senators Joni Ernst, Daniel Sullivan, John McCain, Tom Cotton, Lindsey Graham, and Cory Gardner attending the 2016 International Institute for Strategic Studies Asia Security Summit in Singapore.jpg|thumb|300px|U.S. Secretary of Defense [[Ash Carter]] and Senators [[Joni Ernst]], [[Dan Sullivan (U.S. Senator)|Daniel Sullivan]], [[John McCain]], Tom Cotton, [[Lindsey Graham]], and [[Cory Gardner]] attending the 2016 [[International Institute for Strategic Studies]] Asia Security Summit in Singapore]]\n{{See also|2014 United States Senate election in Arkansas}}\nOn August 6, 2013, Cotton officially announced he would challenge Democratic incumbent [[Mark Pryor]] for his seat in the [[United States Senate]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-250_162-57597296/republican-rep-tom-cotton-announces-bid-to-challenge-sen-mark-pryor-d-ark | title=Republican Rep. Tom Cotton announces bid to challenge Sen. Mark Pryor, D-Ark. | first=Stephanie | last=Condon | publisher=[[CBS News]] | date=August 6, 2013}}</ref> [[Stuart Rothenberg]] of ''[[Roll Call]]'' called Pryor the most vulnerable Senator seeking re-election.<ref>{{cite news | last=Rothenberg | first=Stuart | title=Mark Pryor: Still This Cycle's Most Vulnerable Senator | url=http://blogs.rollcall.com/rothenblog/stu-rothenberg-arkansas-senate-race/ | publisher=[[Roll Call]] | date=June 9, 2014}}</ref> Cotton was endorsed by the conservative [[Club for Growth]] PAC,<ref>{{cite news | last=Gentilviso | first=Chris | title=Tom Cotton 2014 Senate Run Gets Early Club For Growth Endorsement | url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/08/07/tom-cotton-2014_n_3720093.html | work=[[The Huffington Post]] | date=August 7, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last=Judis | first=John | title=The Shrinking Club for Growth | url=https://newrepublic.com/article/115222/shrinking-club-growth | work=[[The New Republic]] | date=October 16, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last=Joseph | first=Cameron | title=Club for Growth endorses Tom Cotton, launches ads in Arkansas Senate race | url=http://thehill.com/video/in-the-news/315915-club-for-growth-endorses-tom-cotton | work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] | date=August 7, 2013}}</ref> Senator [[Marco Rubio]],<ref>{{cite news | last=Strauss | first=Daniel | title=Rubio Endorses Rep. Tom Cotton for Senate | url=http://talkingpointsmemo.com/dc/rubio-endorses-rep-tom-cotton-for-senate | work=[[Talking Points Memo]] | date=September 17, 2013}}</ref> the National Federation of Independent Business,<ref>{{cite news | last=Urban | first=Peter | title=Small-business group endorses Cotton | url=http://arkansasnews.com/news/washington/small-business-group-endorses-cotton | work=[[Stephens Media (newspapers)|Arkansas News]] | date=July 1, 2014}}</ref> and former presidential candidate [[Mitt Romney]], who campaigned for Cotton.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.arktimes.com/ArkansasBlog/archives/2014/08/21/mitt-romney-endorses-tom-cotton | title=Mitt Romney endorses Tom Cotton | first=David | last=Ramsey | publisher=[[Arkansas Times]] | date=August 21, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title=Mitt Romney to campaign for Asa Hutchinson and Tom Cotton; Democrats comment | url=https://www.arktimes.com/ArkansasBlog/archives/2014/08/20/mitt-romney-to-campaign-in-jonesboro-for-asa-hutcinson-democrats-comment/ | first=Max | last=Brantley | work=[[Arkansas Times]] | date=August 20, 2014}}</ref> The Associated Press called the race for Cotton immediately after the polls closed;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2014/11/arkansas-senate-results-elections-2014-tom-cotton-mark-pryor-112515.html|title=Cotton defeats Pryor in Arkansas|first=Katie|last=Glueck|website=POLITICO}}</ref> he prevailed by a margin of 56.5%-39.4%.<ref>https://results.enr.clarityelections.com/AR/53237/149792/Web01/en/summary.html</ref> Cotton was sworn into office on January 6, 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/tom-cotton-trump-cia-director-senator-bio-photos-2017-11|title=Meet Tom Cotton, the Arkansas senator with Trump's ear who graduated from Harvard in 3 years and might become the next head of the CIA|first=Michal|last=Kranz|website=Business Insider}}</ref>\n\n====Committee assignments====\n[[File:Sen. Tom Cotton visits Air Defenders in Korea 150815-A-DY706-004.jpg|thumb|Senator Cotton visits Air Defenders at [[Osan Air Base]] during his three-country tour to [[Japan]], [[South Korea]], and [[Taiwan]]]]\n* '''[[United States Senate Committee on Armed Services]]'''\n**[[United States Senate Armed Services Subcommittee on Airland]] (Chair)\n**[[United States Senate Armed Services Subcommittee on Seapower]]\n**[[United States Senate Armed Services Subcommittee on Strategic Forces]]\n* '''[[United States Senate Committee on Banking, Housing, and Urban Affairs]]'''\n**[[United States Senate Banking Subcommittee on Economic Policy]] (Chair)\n**[[United States Senate Banking Subcommittee on Housing, Transportation, and Community Development]]\n**[[United States Senate Banking Subcommittee on National Security and International Trade and Finance]]\n* '''[[United States Senate Special Committee on Aging]]'''\n* '''[[United States Senate Select Committee on Intelligence]]'''\n* '''[[Joint Economic Committee]]'''\n\n====Cassandra Butts nomination====\nIn February 2015, Obama renominated [[Cassandra Butts]], a former White House lawyer, to be the [[United States Ambassador to the Bahamas|United States ambassador to the Bahamas]]. However, Butts's nomination was blocked by several Republican senators. First, Senator [[Ted Cruz]] placed a blanket hold on all U.S. State Department nominees.<ref name=Butts>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/06/07/opinion/an-obama-nominees-crushed-hopes.html|title=An Obama Nominee's Crushed Hopes|first=Frank|last=Bruni|website=[[The New York Times]]|date=June 7, 2016}}</ref> Cotton specifically blocked the nominations of Butts and ambassador nominees to Sweden and Norway after the Secret Service had leaked private information about a fellow member of Congress, although that issue was unrelated to those nominees. Cotton eventually released his holds on the nominees to Sweden and Norway, but kept his hold on Butts' nomination.<ref name=Butts/>\n\nButts told ''New York Times'' columnist [[Frank Bruni]] that she had gone to see Cotton about his objections to her nomination, and said Cotton had told her that because he knew that the president and Butts were friends, it was a way to \"inflict special pain on the president\", Bruni said. Cotton's spokeswoman did not dispute Butts' characterization. Butts died on May 26, 2016, still awaiting a Senate vote.<ref name=Butts/>\n\n===Potential roles in the Trump administration===\n{{further|Cabinet of Donald Trump}}\nCotton was mentioned as a possible candidate for [[United States Secretary of Defense]] in the [[Presidency of Donald Trump|Trump administration]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.politico.com/blogs/donald-trump-administration/2016/11/donald-trump-cabinet-members-list-of-choices-picks-and-selections-so-far-231444|title=Donald Trump's Cabinet-in-waiting: What we know so far|last=Restuccia|first=Andrew|date=November 18, 2016|work=[[Politico]]|accessdate=November 18, 2016}}</ref> However, retired general [[James Mattis]] was chosen instead.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/administration/308420-trump-announces-mattis-as-defense-pick|title=Trump announces Mattis as Defense pick|last=Byrnes|first=Jesse|date=December 1, 2016|accessdate=December 2, 2016}}</ref> Cotton frequently met with Trump's staff during the transition period, and according to [[Steve Bannon]], Cotton suggested [[John F. Kelly]] for the role of [[United States Secretary of Homeland Security|Secretary of Homeland Security]].<ref name=\"trumpism\" />\n\nIn November 2017, ''[[The New York Times]]'' reported that Cotton was a potential choice to succeed [[CIA Director|CIA director]] [[Mike Pompeo]], who was elevated to [[United States Secretary of State]] after President Trump 'soured' on the then-incumbent, [[Rex Tillerson]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/11/30/us/politics/state-department-tillerson-pompeo-trump.html|title=White House Plans Tillerson Ouster, to Be Replaced by Mike Pompeo, Within Weeks|last=Baker|first=Peter|date=November 30, 2017|work=[[New York Times]]|accessdate=November 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2018, [[Politico]] reported that Cotton was a potential choice to replace [[Jim Mattis]] as [[United States Secretary of Defense]] after Mattis announced his resignation for January 1, 2019.<ref>{{cite news|title=Trump next defense Secretary Mattis replacement|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/12/20/trump-next-defense-secretary-mattis-replacement-1049135|last=)O'Brien|first=Connor|date=December 20, 2018|work=[[Politico]]|accessdate=December 20, 2018}}</ref> Ultimately, Mark Esper was chosen to succeed Mattis on June 18, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/realDonaldTrump/status/1141027595380826118|title=....I thank Pat for his outstanding service and will be naming Secretary of the Army, Mark Esper, to be the new Acting Secretary of Defense. I know Mark, and have no doubt he will do a fantastic job!|last=Trump|first=Donald J.|date=2019-06-18|website=@realDonaldTrump|language=en|access-date=2019-08-10}}</ref>[[File:President Donald J. Trump, Senator Tom Cotton, and Senator David Perdue, August 2, 2017 (36182228582).jpg|thumb|right|300px|Tom Cotton (left) with president [[Donald Trump]] and Republican senator [[David Perdue]] (right).]]\n\n==Political positions==\n===Domestic policy===\n==== Corporate disclosure ====\nIn June 2019, along with Democrats [[Mark Warner]] and [[Doug Jones (politician)|Doug Jones]] and fellow Republican [[Mike Rounds]], Cotton introduced the Improving Laundering Laws and Increasing Comprehensive Information Tracking of Criminal Activity in Shell Holdings (ILLICIT CASH) Act, a bill that would mandate shell companies disclose their real owners to the [[United States Department of the Treasury]] and update outdated federal anti-money laundering laws through bettering communications among law enforcement, regulatory agencies, the financial industry, and the industry and regulators of advanced technology.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://kfgo.com/news/articles/2019/jun/10/us-senators-launch-bill-to-broaden-shell-companies-disclosures/|title=U.S. senators launch bill to broaden shell companies' disclosures|first=Mark|last=Hosenball|date=June 10, 2019|publisher=kfgo.com}}</ref>\n\n====Criminal justice reform====\n[[File:Senator of Arkansas Tom Cotton at NH FITN 2016 by Michael Vadon 08.jpg|thumb|Senator Cotton at First In The Nation Townhall, [[New Hampshire]]]]\nIn 2016, Cotton said that the United States had an \"under-incarceration problem\", as opposed to a problem with over-incarceration.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2016/05/tom-cotton-under-incarceration-223371|title=Sen. Tom Cotton: U.S. has 'under-incarceration problem'|work=POLITICO|access-date=2018-11-15|language=en}}</ref> Cotton said that reduced sentencing for felons would destabilize the United States, arguing that \"I saw this in Baghdad. We\u2019ve seen it again in Afghanistan.\"<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn November 2018, while arguing against a bipartisan criminal justice reform bill, Cotton mistakenly said that there had been no hearings on the bill. PolitiFact noted that Cotton \"ignored years of congressional debate and hearings on the general topics of the bill, as well as the consideration and bipartisan passage of largely similar bills at the House committee level, by the full House, and by the Senate Judiciary Committee.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/statements/2018/nov/20/tom-cotton/were-there-no-hearings-bipartisan-criminal-justice/|title=Were there no hearings on bipartisan criminal justice bill?|work=@politifact|access-date=2018-11-23|language=en}}</ref> Arguing against the bill in question, the [[FIRST STEP Act]], Cotton asserted that \"convicts of certain sex-related crimes could accrue credits making them eligible for supervised release or 'pre-release' to a [[halfway house]]\". A spokesperson for [[Mike Lee (American politician)|Mike Lee]] rebutted that \"just because a federal offense is not on the specific list of ineligible offenses doesn\u2019t mean inmates who committed [a] non-specified offense will earn early release\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=EVERETT |first1=BURGESS |last2=SCHOR |first2=ELANA |title=Cotton wields sex offender report to tank prisons bill |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/11/26/tom-cotton-criminal-justice-reform-senate-republicans-trump-1015149 |website=Politico |accessdate=1 December 2018}}</ref> The bill passed 87-12 on December 18, 2018. Cotton voted against it.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Levin |first1=Marianne |title=Senate approves Trump-backed criminal justice overhaul |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/12/18/criminal-justice-reform-bill-vote-1068268 |website=Politico |accessdate=18 December 2018}}</ref>\n[[File:Tom Cotton and Brett Kavanaugh.jpg|thumb|Tom Cotton and [[Brett Kavanaugh]] in August 2018]]\n\n====Gun laws====\nCotton has an A rating from the [[National Rifle Association]] (NRA), which endorsed him during the 2014 election. The NRA's Chris W. Cox stated that \"Tom Cotton will always stand up for the values and freedoms of Arkansas gun owners and sportsmen.\"<ref>{{cite press release|title=NRA Endorses Tom Cotton for U.S. Senate in Arkansas|url=https://www.nrapvf.org/articles/20140909/nra-endorses-tom-cotton-for-us-senate-in-arkansas|publisher=[[National Rifle Association]]|date=September 9, 2014}}</ref> In response to the [[2017 Las Vegas shooting]], Cotton stated that he did not believe any new gun control legislation would have prevented the mass shooting from taking place.<ref>{{cite news|last=Shelbourne|first=Mallory|title=Cotton: Las Vegas shooter's weapon sounded like 'belt-fed machine gun'|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/senate/353589-cotton-las-vegas-shooters-weapon-sounded-like-belt-fed-machine-gun|work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]|date=October 3, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2019, Cotton was one of thirty-one Republican senators to cosponsor the Constitutional Concealed Carry Reciprocity Act, a bill introduced by [[John Cornyn]] and [[Ted Cruz]] that would grant individuals with concealed carry privileges in their home state the right to exercise this right in any other state with concealed carry laws while concurrently abiding by that state's laws.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.kcbd.com/2019/01/10/sens-cruz-cornyn-file-concealed-carry-reciprocity-bill/|title=Sens. Cruz, Cornyn file Concealed-Carry Reciprocity Bill|date=January 10, 2019|publisher=kcbd.com}}</ref>\n\n====Healthcare====\nCotton opposes the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act|Affordable Care Act]] (Obamacare), saying in 2012 that \"the first step is to repeal that law, which is offensive to a free society and a free people\".<ref>{{cite news|title=4th District hopefuls split on health care law|url=http://www.couriernews.com/view/full_story/20271348/article-4th-District-hopefuls-split-on-health-care-law|agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=September 26, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Ramsey|first=David|title=How Tom Cotton talks when he talks about Obamacare|url=http://www.arktimes.com/ArkansasBlog/archives/2014/04/18/how-tom-cotton-talks-when-he-talks-about-obamacare|work=[[Arkansas Times]]|date=April 14, 2014}}</ref> In April 2014, Cotton was one of 38 Republican lawmakers that signed an ''[[amicus curiae]]'' in support of Senator [[Ron Johnson (Wisconsin politician)|Ron Johnson]]'s legal challenge against the [[United States Office of Personnel Management]]'s ACA ruling.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-politics/wp/2014/04/22/38-gop-lawmakers-join-ron-johnsons-obamacare-lawsuit|title=38 GOP lawmakers join Ron Johnson's Obamacare lawsuit|first=Ed|last=O'Keefe|website=[[The Washington Post]]|date=April 24, 2014}}{{subscription required}}</ref>\n\nCotton was part of the group of 13 Republican Senators that drafted the [[2017 Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act replacement proposals#Senate legislation|Senate version]] of the [[American Health Care Act of 2017]] (AHCA) behind closed doors.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/05/05/politics/senate-republican-health-care-men/index.html|title=GOP defends having no women in health care group|last1=Bash|first1=Dana|last2=Fox|first2=Lauren|last3=Barrett|first3=Ted|work=[[CNN]]|date=May 9, 2017}}</ref>\n\n====Immigration====\nCotton opposes amnesty or a path to citizenship for undocumented immigrants.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tom Cotton on Immigration|url=http://www.ontheissues.org/House/Tom_Cotton_Immigration.htm|website=[[On the Issues]]}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2013, after the Senate's bipartisan [[Gang of Eight (immigration)|Gang of Eight]] passed the [[Border Security, Economic Opportunity, and Immigration Modernization Act of 2013]], an immigration reform proposal, House Republicans held a closed door meeting to decide whether to bring the bill to a vote.<ref name=flank>{{cite news|last=Costa|first=Robert|title=Picking Tom Cotton: On immigration, a freshman speaks for the right flank of the House GOP|url=http://www.nationalreview.com/article/353386/picking-tom-cotton-robert-costa|work=[[The National Review]]|date=July 15, 2013}}</ref> Budget Committee chairman [[Paul Ryan]] spoke at one podium arguing for the bill's passage.<ref name=newyorker16>{{cite news|last=Lizza|first=Ryan|title=Occupied Territory: The Republican \u00e9lite struggles over whether to resist Trump or capitulate|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2016/06/20/inside-the-gop-trump-dilemma|work=[[The New Yorker]]|date=July 20, 2016}}</ref> Cotton spoke at another podium arguing against the bill, even exchanging terse comments with Speaker Boehner.<ref name=flank/> Cotton noted that a tougher stance on immigration had done little to diminish [[Mitt Romney]]'s electoral support among Hispanics in 2012 compared to [[John McCain]]'s in 2008. The House decided to not consider the bill.<ref name=newyorker16/>\n\n[[File:Letter from the staff of US Senator Tom Cotton (R-Arkansas) advising people to not call or write.jpg|thumb|300px|Activists had been urging the senator via phone calls and letters to support positions regarding issues such as health care and immigration. The senator's office sent letters asking some of them to cease-and-desist from such contacts, or else the office would contact the US Capitol Police.<ref name=twsArkNews1>Max Brantley, January 18, 2018, Arkansas Times, [https://www.arktimes.com/ArkansasBlog/archives/2018/01/18/activists-say-tom-cotton-has-a-do-not-call-or-write-list-for-some-constituents Activists say Tom Cotton has issued do-not-call-or-write notice to some constituents. UPDATE. Such letters sent in 'extreme circumstances' says Cotton's office.], Retrieved January 18, 2018, \"...Fleming said he knew several people who'd received such a letter. He said he believed they all had made repeated phone calls to deliver similar talking points, but he said they were unlikely to have made rude or disparaging remarks.....\"</ref>]]\nCotton supported President Trump's 2017 [[Executive Order 13769]] that prohibited immigration from seven predominantly Muslim countries.<ref>{{cite news|last=Blake|first=Aaron|title=Coffman, Gardner join Republicans against President Trump's travel ban; here's where the rest stand|url=http://www.denverpost.com/2017/01/29/republicans-on-trump-travel-ban|work=[[The Denver Post]]|date=January 29, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn February 7, 2017, in the presence of President Trump, Cotton and Senator [[David Perdue]] (R-[[Georgia (U.S. state)|GA]]), jointly proposed a new immigration bill called the [[RAISE Act]] which would limit the family route or [[chain migration]]. The bill would set a limit on the number of refugees offered residency at 50,000 a year and would remove the [[Diversity Immigrant Visa]]. Senators [[Lindsey Graham]] (R-SC) and [[John McCain]] (R-AZ) both expressed opposition to the bill.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/news/united-states/21717106-reforming-legal-immigration-new-effort-narrow-route-permanent-residency|title=A new effort to narrow the route to permanent residency in America|work=[[The Economist]]|date=February 16, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2017/08/can-a-decades-old-immigration-proposal-pass-under-trump/537138|title=Can a Decades-Old Immigration Proposal Pass Under Trump?|first=Priscilla|last=Alvarez|work=[[The Atlantic]]|date=August 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAfter the violent incidents surrounding the [[2017 Unite the Right rally]], Cotton issued a statement condemning white [[supremacism]].<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://www.cotton.senate.gov/?p=press_release&id=769|title=Cotton Statement on the Violence in Charlottesville|publisher=[[United States Senate]]|date=August 13, 2017}}</ref>{{Better source|date=May 2019}}\n\nCotton, a supporter of President [[Donald Trump]] on the issue of immigration, was at a meeting in which Cotton disputes an alleged attribution that described [[Haiti]] and [[List of sovereign states and dependent territories in Africa|African nations]] as \"shithole countries\".<ref>Ali Vitali,  [https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/white-house/trump-referred-haiti-african-countries-shithole-nations-n836946 Trump referred to Haiti and African nations as 'shithole' countries], NBCnews.com, January 12, 2017.</ref> Cotton's statements were predicated on his assertion that his colleagues, Sen. [[Dick Durbin]] (D-IL) and Sen. [[Lindsey Graham]] (R-SC), lied in their statements that the President had in fact disparaged those nations and peoples in the January 11 meeting, and that the President's language had been salacious, including derogatory curse words that persons on all sides of the incident had described as \"vulgar\".<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/sen-cotton-says-trumps-words-sentiments-on-immigration-were-misrepresented/ |title = Sen. Tom Cotton says Trump's words, sentiments on immigration were misrepresented}}</ref> Cotton and Senator [[David Perdue]] (R-GA)  said in a joint statement that \"we do not recall the President saying these comments specifically\".<ref name=\"twsCNN494\">Ashley Killough, January 12, 2017, CNN, [http://www.cnn.com/2018/01/12/politics/senators-trump-comment-tom-cotton/index.html 2 Republican senators in Trump meeting say they don't recall 'shithole' comment]<br />\"...We do not recall the President saying these comments specifically but what he did call out was the imbalance in our current immigration system,...\"</ref><ref name=\"twsNYPost494\">Ruth Brown, January 12, 2017, New York Post, [https://nypost.com/2018/01/12/gop-lawmakers-dont-recall-trumps-shithole-slur \"GOP lawmakers 'do not recall' Trump's 'shithole' slur\"], Retrieved January 14, 2017, \"...Republican Sens. David Perdue and Tom Cotton say they \"don't recall\" President Trump \"specifically\" smearing Haiti and African nations as \"shitholes\" ...\"</ref> ''[[The Washington Post]]'' reported that Cotton and Perdue told the White House they heard \"shithouse\" rather than \"shithole\".<ref name=\"Wash Post 2018-01-15\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/inside-the-tense-profane-white-house-meeting-on-immigration/2018/01/15/13e79fa4-fa1e-11e7-8f66-2df0b94bb98a_story.html|title=Inside the tense, profane White House meeting on immigration|last1=Dawsey|first1=Josh|date=January 15, 2018|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|last2=Costa|first2=Robert|last3=Parker|first3=Ashley}}</ref> Sen. Cotton reiterated on CBS's \"Face The Nation\" interview \"I certainly didn\u2019t hear what Sen. Durbin has said repeatedly. Sen. Durbin has a history of misrepresenting what happens in White House meetings, though, so perhaps we shouldn\u2019t be surprised by that,\u201d Cotton added, \u201cAnd I was sitting no farther away from Donald Trump than Dick Durbin was, and I know what Dick Durbin has said about the president's repeated statements is incorrect\u201d.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://thehill.com/homenews/sunday-talk-shows/368963-cotton-attacks-durbin-for-claims-of-trumps-shithole-countries |title = Cotton hits Durbin for claims of Trump's 's---hole countries' comment|date = January 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2018, Cotton placed a senatorial hold on [https://www.congress.gov/bill/115th-congress/house-bill/7164 H.R.7164] - A Bill to add Ireland to the E-3 Non-immigrant Visa Program.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irishcentral.com/news/politics/e3-bill-dies-thanks-to-senator-tom-cotton-and-incredibly-an-irish-journalist-neil-munro|title=E3 bill dies thanks to Senator Tom Cotton and incredibly, an Irish journalist Neil Munro|date=2018-12-21|website=IrishCentral.com|language=en|access-date=2018-12-22}}</ref> The bill did not create new non-immigrant visas, but rather allowed Irish college graduates to apply for any surplus E-3 visas in Specialty Occupations, that had gone unused by Australians within their annual cap of 10,500.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irishcentral.com/news/politics/what-is-e3-bill-what-would-it-mean-for-irish|title=What is the E3 visa and what does it mean to the Irish?|date=2018-12-04|website=IrishCentral.com|language=en|access-date=2018-12-20}}</ref> The bi-partisan bill which had passed the House of Representatives on November 28, 2018 and had also received the backing of the Trump Administration, particularly then Chief of Staff [[John F. Kelly|John Kelly]] and Director of the Office of Management and Budget (and then incoming chief of staff) [[Mick Mulvaney]]. Despite the backing of a broad collation within congress, H.R.7164 did not reach the Senate floor for consideration under unanimous consent as a consequence of Sen. Cotton's hold.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irishcentral.com/news/irish-e3-visas-senator-tom-cotton|title=Irish E3 visas face further blow as another senator places hold on bill|date=2018-12-20|website=IrishCentral.com|language=en|access-date=2018-12-20}}</ref> Press reports indicate that Sen. Cotton refused to engage with Irish leaders during the process by not taking phone calls from Irish deputy prime minister [[Simon Coveney]] and sending his chief of staff in his place to a scheduled meeting at the [[Embassy of Ireland, Washington, D.C.]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irishcentral.com/opinion/niallodowd/senator-tom-cotton-refused-irish-leader-phone-calls-e3-irish-visas|title=Senator Tom Cotton refused to take Irish leader phone calls on E3 Irish visas|date=2018-12-22|website=IrishCentral.com|language=en|access-date=2018-12-22}}</ref> Sen. Cotton has not to date offered an explanation of his hold on the legislation.\n\nIn February 2019, Cotton was one of sixteen senators to vote against legislation preventing a partial government shutdown and containing 1.375 billion for barriers along the U.S.-Mexico border that included 55 miles of fencing.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/senate/430076-senate-approves-border-bill|title=Senate approves border bill that prevents shutdown|first=Jordain|last=Carney|publisher=The Hill}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2019, after President Trump announced a two-week delay for a plan involving the deportation of an estimated 2,000 migrant families as part of an attempt to give Congress a chance to work on immigration reform, Cotton stated his support for Trump's plan and questioned who the United States could deport if it was unable to \"deport an illegal alien who has a final and legal order of removal adjudicated by an immigration judge\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/sunday-talk-shows/449910-cotton-healthy-skepticism-warranted-when-dealing-with-democrats-on|title=Cotton: 'Healthy skepticism warranted' when dealing with Democrats on immigration|date=June 23, 2019|publisher=The Hill}}</ref>\n\n==== Infrastructure ====\nIn February 2019, Cotton was one of eleven senators to sign a letter to [[United States Secretary of Energy|Energy Secretary]] [[Rick Perry]] and [[United States Secretary of Homeland Security|Homeland Security Secretary]] [[Kirstjen Nielsen]] urging them \"to work with all federal, state and local regulators, as well as the hundreds of independent power producers and electricity distributors nation-wide to ensure our systems are protected\" and affirming that they were \"ready and willing to provide any assistance you need to secure our critical electricity infrastructure.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://thehill.com/policy/cybersecurity/431427-senators-request-trump-admin-consider-ban-on-huawei-tech-in-us-electric|title=Key senators say administration should ban Huawei tech in US electric grid|first=Jacqueline|last=Thomsen|date=February 25, 2019|publisher=The Hill}}</ref>\n\n====Minimum wage====\nAfter not taking a position on [[minimum wage]] during his campaign, in September 2014, Cotton said he would vote, as a citizen, in favor of the Arkansas Minimum Wage Initiative, a November 2014 referendum to raise Arkansas's minimum wage from $6.25 an hour to $8.50 an hour by 2017. Cotton was criticized for failing to take a public position on the issue until public opinion was overwhelmingly in favor.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/09/05/tom-cotton-minimum-wage_n_5772246.html|title=Tom Cotton Says He Will Vote For Minimum Wage Hike 'As A Citizen'|first=Igor|last=Bobic|work=[[The Huffington Post]]|date=September 5, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.arktimes.com/ArkansasBlog/archives/2014/09/28/the-not-so-principled-stand-of-tom-cotton-on-the-minimum-wage|title=The not-so-principled stand of Tom Cotton on the minimum wage|first=David|last=Ramsey|work=[[Arkansas Times]]|date=September 28, 2014}}</ref>\n\n====Social issues====\nIn June 2013, Cotton voted in favor of the [[Pain-Capable Unborn Child Protection Act]], a bill to ban [[abortion]]s occurring 20 or more weeks after fertilization.<ref>{{cite web|title=House Vote 251 \u2013 Approves New Abortion Restrictions|url=http://politics.nytimes.com/congress/votes/113/house/1/251|website=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> Cotton has stated that \"I believe ''[[Roe v. Wade]]'' and ''[[Planned Parenthood v. Casey]]'' were wrongly decided.\"<ref name=abortion/> He was one of 183 co-sponsors of the version of the Title X Abortion Provider Prohibition Act introduced in 2013.<ref>{{cite web|title=H.R.217 - Title X Abortion Provider Prohibition Act|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/113th-congress/house-bill/217/cosponsors|website=[[United States Congress]]|year=2013}}</ref>\n\nCotton has stated \"I oppose the destruction of human embryos to conduct stem-cell research and all forms of human cloning.\"<ref name=abortion>{{cite web|title=Tom Cotton on Abortion|url=http://www.ontheissues.org/Social/Tom_Cotton_Abortion.htm|website=[[On the Issues]]|accessdate=January 19, 2018}}</ref> In 2012, Cotton said, \"Strong families also depend on strong marriages, and I support the traditional understanding of marriage as the union of one man and one woman. I also support the [[Defense of Marriage Act]].\"<ref name=civilrights>{{cite web|title=Tom Cotton on Civil Rights|url=http://www.ontheissues.org/House/Tom_Cotton_Civil_Rights.htm|website=[[On the Issues]]|accessdate=January 19, 2018}}</ref> In 2013, Cotton voted against reauthorizing the [[Violence Against Women Act]].<ref name=civilrights/>\n\nIn September 2013, Cotton was one of 103 co-sponsors of the Marriage and Religious Freedom Act.<ref>{{cite web|title=H.R.3133 - Marriage and Religious Freedom Act|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/113th-congress/house-bill/3133|website=[[United States Congress]]|date=September 19, 2013}}</ref> In October 2015, Cotton was one of 24 co-sponsors of the Thin Blue Line Act, a federal bill that would impose the [[death penalty]] in the case of the killing of police officers.<ref>{{cite web|title=S.2034 - Thin Blue Line Act|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/114th-congress/senate-bill/2034/cosponsors|website=[[United States Congress]]|date=September 15, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2019, Cotton publicly decried the [[Southern Poverty Law Center]] as being a \"political hate group\" and asked the IRS to check if the SPLC should retain its tax-exempt status.<ref>\ud83d\udd89{{Cite web|url=https://www.apnews.com/eb55ef89f07e540909cd5e8449fbca84|title=Tom Cotton calls for IRS to investigate Southern Poverty Law Center's tax-exempt status|first=Valerie Richardson The Washington|last=Times|date=April 3, 2019|website=AP NEWS}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2019, along with [[Pat Toomey]] and [[Todd Young]], Cotton introduced the Government Bailout Prevention Act, a bill that would prohibit any arm of the federal government including the Federal Reserve System and Treasury Department from paying or guaranteeing state and local obligations in the event that state or local government entities file bankruptcy, default on  debts or are at risk of bankruptcy or default. Cotton said the bill \"would ensure American taxpayers aren\u2019t stuck with the tab for the spending binges of a few irresponsible politicians.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://pennbizreport.com/news/13654-sens-toomey-young-cotton-introduce-bill-to-prevent-government-bailouts/|title=Sens. Toomey, Young, Cotton introduce bill to prevent government bailouts|date=July 22, 2019|first=Kevin|last=Randolph|publisher=Pennsylvania Business Report}}</ref>\n\n====Student loans====\nIn August 2013, Cotton voted against the Bipartisan Student Loan Certainty Act of 2013, which lowered interest rates on [[student loan]]s. Cotton had received federally-subsidized student loans when he was a student but said he did not want the government in the student loan business, noting that he and his family worked for years to afford his college education.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/08/01/tom-cotton-student-loans_n_3692026.html|title=Tom Cotton, Arkansas Rep., Took Student Loans, Voted Against Them|first=Michael|last=McAuliff|work=[[The Huffington Post]]|date=August 1, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Foreign policy===\n[[File:US congressional delegation at HISF 2014.jpg|thumb|US congressional delegation at [[Halifax International Security Forum]] 2014]]\nCotton's foreign policy views have been characterized as \"[[War hawk|hawkish]]\".<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/senate/443725-cotton-us-could-win-war-with-iran-in-two-strikes|title=Cotton: US could win war with Iran in 'two strikes'|last=Axelrod|first=Tal|date=2019-05-14|website=TheHill|language=en|access-date=2019-05-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title= A Foreign Policy for 'Jacksonian America' |journal= [[The Wall Street Journal]] |url= https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-foreign-policy-for-jacksonian-america-1512774761 |date= December 9\u201310, 2017 |last= Willick |first= Jason  |accessdate= August 5, 2018 }} {{subscription required}}</ref>\n\nDuring a February 5, 2015 [[United States Senate Committee on Armed Services|Senate Armed Services Committee]] hearing, Cotton called for housing more prisoners at [[Guantanamo Bay detention camp|Guantanamo Bay]] instead of closing it. He also said of the prisoners in the camp \"...every last one them can rot in hell, but as long as they don't do that they can rot in Guantanamo Bay\".<ref>{{Citation|title=February 5, 2015: Sen. Tom Cotton SASC Q&A on Guantanamo Bay facilities|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oIEJbCAK3qQ|language=en|access-date=2019-08-20}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2016, Cotton was one of thirty-four senators to sign a letter to [[United States Secretary of State|United States secretary of state]] [[John Kerry]] advocating for the United States using \"all available tools to dissuade Russia from continuing its airstrikes in Syria\" from an [[List of Iranian Air Force bases|Iranian airbase]] near [[Hamadan]] \"that are clearly not in our interest\" and stating that there should be clear enforcement by the US of the airstrikes violating \"a legally binding Security Council Resolution\" on Iran.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://thehill.com/policy/defense/296603-gop-pressures-kerry-on-russias-use-of-iranian-airbase|title=GOP pressures Kerry on Russia's use of Iranian airbase|date=September 19, 2016|first=Rebecca|last=Kheel|publisher=The Hill}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2017, Cotton voted in favor of the [[Countering America's Adversaries Through Sanctions Act]] that grouped together [[International sanctions|sanctions]] against [[Russia]], [[Iran]] and [[North Korea]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.senate.gov/legislative/LIS/roll_call_lists/roll_call_vote_cfm.cfm?congress=115&session=1&vote=00175|title=U.S. Senate: U.S. Senate Roll Call Votes 115th Congress - 1st Session|website=www.senate.gov|date=July 27, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2017, Cotton co-sponsored the [[Israel Anti-Boycott Act]] (S.270), which made it a federal crime, punishable by a maximum sentence of 20 years imprisonment,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2017/07/senate-bill-would-make-it-a-federal-crime-to-boycott-israel.html|title=43 Senators Want to Make It a Federal Crime to Boycott Israeli Settlements |last=Levitz|first=Eric|date=2017-07-19|website=Intelligencer|language=en}}</ref> for Americans to encourage or participate in boycotts against Israel and [[Israeli settlement]]s in the occupied [[Israeli-occupied territories|Palestinian territories]] if protesting actions by the Israeli government.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/115th-congress/senate-bill/720/cosponsors|title=Cosponsors - S.720 - 115th Congress (2017-2018): Israel Anti-Boycott Act|date=23 March 2017|website=www.congress.gov}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2018, after President Trump announced the withdrawal of [[American-led intervention in the Syrian Civil War|American troops in Syria]], Cotton was one of six senators to sign a letter expressing concern for the move and their belief \"that such action at this time is a premature and costly mistake that not only threatens the safety and security of the United States, but also emboldens ISIS, Bashar al Assad, Iran, and Russia.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/senate/422208-bipartisan-senators-call-on-trump-to-reconsider-syria-withdrawal|title=Senators call on Trump administration to reconsider Syria withdrawal|date=December 19, 2018|publisher=The Hill}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2019, Cotton was one of eleven Republican senators to vote to advance legislation intended to block President Trump's intent to lift sanctions against three Russian companies.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://thehill.com/blogs/floor-action/senate/425506-senate-advances-measure-bucking-trump-on-russia-sanctions|title=Senate advances measure bucking Trump on Russia sanctions|date=January 15, 2019|publisher=The Hill}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2019, Cotton revealed he suggested to Trump and the Danish ambassador that the U.S. should buy [[Greenland]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Field |first1=Hunter |last2=Lockwood |first2=Frank E. |date=August 22, 2019 |title=U.S. Sen. Tom Cotton backs buying Greenland, says he floated idea to Trump, Danish ambassador |url=https://www.arkansasonline.com/news/2019/aug/22/cotton-backs-buying-greenland-20190822/ |work=[[Arkansas Democrat-Gazette]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n| last         = Sonmez\n| first        = Felicia\n| date         = August 22, 2019\n| title        = Sen. Tom Cotton says he mentioned buying Greenland to Trump, Danish ambassador\n| url          = https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/sen-cotton-says-he-raised-the-idea-of-buying-greenland-in-conversations-with-trump-and-danish-ambassador/2019/08/22/be764f5c-c500-11e9-b5e4-54aa56d5b7ce_story.html\n| work         = [[The Washington Post]]\n| location     = \n| quote        = The revelation came a day after President Trump called off a trip to Denmark because, he said, the country\u2019s leader was not interested in selling Greenland to the United States.\n}}</ref>\n\nCotton supports U.S. withdrawal from the [[Treaty on Open Skies|Open Skies]] agreement, which lets nations use special aircraft to monitor each other's military activities. In 2018, Cotton asserted that the agreement was outdated and that it favored the interests of Russia.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wired.com/story/trump-open-skies-withdrawal/|title=Trump Takes Aim at the 'Open Skies' Cold War Treaty With Russia|work=Wired|access-date=2019-10-14|language=en|issn=1059-1028}}</ref>\n\n==== China ====\nIn 2018, Cotton was a cosponsor of the Countering the Chinese Government and Communist Party's Political Influence Operations Act, a bill introduced by [[Marco Rubio]] and [[Catherine Cortez Masto]] that would grant the U.S. Secretary of State and the Director of National Intelligence (DNI) the authority to create an interagency task force with the purpose of examining attempts by China to influence the U.S. and key allies.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sunshinestatenews.com/story/marco-rubio-catherine-cortez-masto-take-aim-china-new-legislation|title=Marco Rubio, Catherine Cortez Masto Take Aim at China in New Legislation|first=Kevin|last=Derby|publisher=Sunshine State News}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2018, Cotton and 16 other lawmakers urged the Trump administration to impose sanctions under the Global Magnitsky Act against [[Communist Party of China|Chinese officials]] who are responsible for [[Xinjiang re-education camps|human rights violations]] in western [[People's Republic of China|China]]'s [[Xinjiang]] region targeting the [[Uyghurs|Uyghur]] ethnic minority.<ref>{{cite web |title=Chairs Lead Bipartisan Letter Urging Administration to Sanction Chinese Officials Complicit in Xinjiang Abuses |url=https://www.cecc.gov/media-center/press-releases/chairs-lead-bipartisan-letter-urging-administration-to-sanction-chinese |website=www.cecc.gov |publisher=Congressional-Executive Commission on China (CECC)}}</ref> They wrote in a bipartisan letter: \"The detention of as many as a million or more Uyghurs and other predominantly Muslim ethnic minorities in \"political reeducation\u201d centers or camps requires a tough, targeted, and global response.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=China rejects US lawmakers' sanctions call over Muslim camps |url=https://www.apnews.com/22e2fb42383a401ab9a401aa69f79257 |agency=Associated Press |date=August 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2017, Cotton was part of a group of Senate Republicans that signed a letter to [[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives|Speaker of the House of Representatives]] [[Nancy Pelosi]] requesting Pelosi invite [[President of Taiwan]] [[Tsai Ing-wen]] to address a joint meeting of Congress. The request came amid heightened tensions between the US and China and was seen as angering Chinese leadership if extended by Pelosi.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-china-congress/republican-u-s-senators-want-taiwan-president-to-address-congress-idUSKCN1PW237|title=Republican U.S. senators want Taiwan president to address Congress|date=February 7, 2019|publisher=Reuters}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2019, when asked about the impact of tariffs on farmers in Arkansas, Cotton admitted there would be \"some sacrifices on the part of Americans, I grant you that, but I also would say that sacrifice is pretty minimal compared to the sacrifices that our soldiers make overseas that are fallen heroes that are laid to rest in Arlington make\" and that farmers were willing to make sacrifices in order for the United States to fend off against Chinese attempts to displace the US globally.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/tom-cotton-says-sacrifice-of-americans-paying-tariffs-is-minimal-compared-to-those-serving-overseas/|title=Tom Cotton says sacrifice of Americans paying tariffs is \"minimal\" compared to those serving overseas|first=Emily|last=Tillett|date=May 13, 2019|publisher=CBS News}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2019, Cotton was a cosponsor of the South China Sea and East China Sea Sanctions Act, a bipartisan bill reintroduced by [[Marco Rubio]] and [[Ben Cardin]] that was intended to disrupt China's consolidation or expansion of its claims of jurisdiction over both the sea and air space in disputed zones in the South China Sea.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/world/united-states/bill-introduced-to-deter-china-in-south-china-east-china-seas|title=US Bill reintroduced to deter China in South China, East China seas|first=Nirmal|last=Ghosh|date=May 24, 2019|publisher=The Straits Times}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2019, Cotton and Democrat [[Chris Van Hollen]] were the primary sponsors of the Defending America's 5G Future Act, a bill that would prevent Huawei from being removed from the \"entity list\" of the Commerce Department without an act of Congress and authorize Congress to block administration waivers for U.S. companies to do business with Huawei. The bill would also codify President Trump's executive order from the previous May that empowered his administration to block foreign tech companies deemed a national security threat from conducting business in the United States.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://thehill.com/policy/cybersecurity/453290-lawmakers-introduce-bill-to-block-us-companies-from-doing-business-with|title=Lawmakers introduce bill to block U.S. companies from doing business with Huawei|first=Maggie|last=Miller|date=July 16, 2019|publisher=The Hill}}</ref>\n\n===== Coronavirus =====\n\nCotton was the first member of Congress to warn about the [[Coronavirus disease 2019]]. By 22 January, he was warning about the virus. On 28 January, he urged the Trump Administration to halt commercial flights from China to the United states due to the developing threat of the virus. On 31 January, spurred in part by Cotton's warnings, the Trump Administration did ban most travel from China.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nationalreview.com/2020/03/the-senator-who-saw-the-coronavirus-coming/|title=The Senator who saw the Coronavirus Coming|work=National Review|author=John McCormack\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=letter|url=https://www.cotton.senate.gov/files/documents/200128_Senator%20Cotton_Coronavirus_Letter.pdf|author=Tom Cotton}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/03/30/how-coronavirus-shook-congress-complacency-155058|work=Politico|author=Natasha Bertrand|date=March 31, 2020|accessdate=April 4, 2020|title=From distraction to disaster: How coronavirus crept up on Washington}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usnews.com/news/politics/articles/2020-03-31/mcconnell-impeachment-diverted-attention-from-coronavirus|title=McConnell: Impeachment 'Diverted Attention' From Coronavirus|work=U.S. News|author=Matthew Daly|accessdate=April 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\nDuring a February 17, 2020 Fox News interview, Cotton said that the corona virus may have started in a \"...biosafety level 4 super laboratory\" in [[Wuhan]], China. \"Now we don\u2019t have evidence that this disease originated there,\" Cotton said, \"but because of China\u2019s duplicity and dishonesty from the beginning we need to at least ask the question.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Fordham |first1=Evrie |title=China 'still lying' about coronavirus outbreak: Sen. Tom Cotton |url=https://www.foxbusiness.com/politics/coronavirus-covid-outbreak-tom-cotton |website=Fox News |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> Subsequently, Cotton was widely criticized for promoting a \"conspiracy theory\" about the virus,<ref>{{Cite news|last=Stevenson|first=Alexandra|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/17/business/media/coronavirus-tom-cotton-china.html|title=Senator Tom Cotton Repeats Fringe Theory of Coronavirus Origins|date=2020-02-17|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-13|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> despite the fact that in 2018, US diplomats had sent warnings to Washington \"...about safety and management weaknesses at the Wuhan Institute of Virology (WIV)\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ricon |first1=Paul |title=Coronavirus: Is there any evidence for lab release theory? |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/science-environment-52318539 |website=BBC News |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>, \n\nWeeks later, multiple media outlets reported that U.S. intelligence officials were investigating the possibility that the virus started in the lab identified by Cotton.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Dilanian |first1=Ken |title=U.S. intel community examining whether coronavirus emerged accidentally from a Chinese lab |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/china/u-s-intel-community-examining-whether-coronavirus-emerged-accidentally-chinese-n1185371 |website=NBC News |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Strobel |first1=Warren P. |title=U.S. Intelligence Sifts Evidence for Origins of Coronavirus |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-intelligence-sifts-evidence-for-origins-of-coronavirus-11587077170 |website=The Wall Street Journal |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> An April 16, 2020 CNN story said that \"An intelligence official familiar with the government analysis said a theory US intelligence officials are investigating is that the virus originated in a laboratory in Wuhan, China, and was accidentally released to the public.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Campbell |first1=Josh |title=US explores possibility that coronavirus spread started in Chinese lab, not a market |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/15/politics/us-intelligence-virus-started-chinese-lab/index.html |website=CNN |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> Cotton has said he would hold China \"accountable\" for what it had done.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/tom-cotton-hold-china-accountable-for-coronavirus-2020-3|title=Republican senator: It's time to hold China 'accountable' for the coronavirus|last=Choi|first=David|website=Business Insider|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref>\n\n====Iran====\n[[File:Secretary Pompeo Delivers Remarks on \"Supporting Iranian Voices\u201d (41773488870).jpg|thumb|Cotton and Secretary of State [[Mike Pompeo]] in July 2018]]\nIn 2013, Cotton introduced legislative language to prohibit trade with relatives of individuals subject to [[U.S. sanctions against Iran]]. According to Cotton, this would include \"a spouse and any relative to the third degree,\" such as, \"parents, children, aunts, uncles, nephews, nieces, grandparents, great grandparents, grandkids, great grandkids.\" After Cotton's amendment came under harsh criticism regarding its constitutionality, he withdrew it.<ref>{{cite news|last=Waldman| first=Paul|title=For Tom Cotton, letter to Iran is anything but a 'fiasco'|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/plum-line/wp/2015/03/11/for-tom-cotton-letter-to-iran-is-anything-but-a-fiasco|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=March 11, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Carter|first=Zach|title=Here's Why Republicans Love Tom Cotton's Letter To Iran|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2015/03/17/americans-dont-like-tom-c_n_6887896.html|work=[[The Huffington Post]]|date=March 17, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2015, Cotton wrote and sent [[s:An Open Letter to the Leaders of the Islamic Republic of Iran|a letter to the leadership of the Islamic Republic of Iran]], signed by 47 of the Senate's 54 Republicans, casting doubt on the Obama administration's authority to engage in [[Comprehensive agreement on Iranian nuclear program|nuclear-proliferation negotiations with Iran]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/03/10/world/asia/white-house-faults-gop-senators-letter-to-irans-leaders.html|title=Angry White House and G.O.P. Senators Clash Over Letter to Iran|last=Baker|first=Peter|date=March 9, 2015|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> The open letter was released in English as well as a poorly-translated Farsi version, which \"read like a middle schooler wrote it\", according to ''[[Foreign Policy]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2015/03/30/sen-tom-cottons-farsi-version-of-his-explosive-letter-to-iranian-leaders-reads-like-a-middle-schooler-wrote-it|title=Sen. Tom Cotton's Farsi Version Of His Explosive Letter to Iranian Leaders Reads Like a Middle Schooler Wrote It|date=March 30, 2015|work=[[Foreign Policy]]}}</ref> Within hours, commentators<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2015/03/logan-act-tom-cotton-iran-116036 |title=Iran, Tom Cotton and the Bizarre History of the Logan Act |last=Zeitz|first=Josh|date=March 12, 2015|work=[[Politico]]}}</ref>{{clarify|date=January 2018}} suggested that the letter prepared by Cotton constituted a violation of the [[Logan Act]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/plum-line/wp/2015/03/09/republicans-are-beginning-to-act-as-though-barack-obama-isnt-even-the-president|title=Republicans are beginning to act as though Barack Obama isn't even the president|last=Waldman|first=Paul|date=March 9, 2015|work=[[The Washington Post]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/the-fix/wp/2015/03/09/what-an-18th-century-non-war-with-france-has-to-do-with-the-senates-letter-to-iran|title=What an 18th century non-war with France has to do with the Senate's letter to Iran|last=Bump|first=Philip|date=March 9, 2015|work=[[The Washington Post]]}}</ref> Questions also were raised as to whether it reflected a flawed interpretation of the [[Treaty Clause]] of the United States Constitution.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/03/09/politics/gop-senators-letter-to-iran|title=Obama, Iranian official slam GOP letter on deal|last=Jaffe|first=Alexandra|date=March 11, 2015|publisher=[[CNN]]}}</ref>\n\nPresident [[Barack Obama]] mocked the letter, referring to it as an \"unusual coalition\" with the [[Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps]] as well as an interference with the then-ongoing negotiations of a comprehensive agreement on the Iranian nuclear program.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-31796235|title=Obama mocks Republican letter to Iran over nuclear talks|date=March 9, 2015|publisher=[[BBC News]]}}</ref> In addition, Obama said, \"I'm embarrassed for them. For them to address a letter to the Ayatollah \u2013 the Supreme Leader of Iran, who they claim is our mortal enemy \u2013 and their basic argument to them is: don't deal with our President, 'cause you can't trust him to follow through on an agreement ... That's close to unprecedented.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2015/03/13/obama-iran-letter_n_6864134.html|title=Obama: 'I'm Embarrassed' For Republicans Who Sent Letter To Iran|last=Lavender|first=Paige|date=March 13, 2015|work=[[The Huffington Post]]}}</ref>\n\nIran's foreign minister, [[Javad Zarif]], responded to the letter by saying \"[the senators'] letter in fact undermines the credibility of thousands of such mere executive agreements that have been or will be entered into by the US with various other governments\". Zarif pointed out that the nuclear deal is not supposed to be an Iran\u2013US deal, but an international one, saying that \"change of administration does not in any way relieve the next administration from international obligations undertaken by its predecessor in a possible agreement about Iran's peaceful nuclear program.\" He continued, \"I wish to enlighten the authors that if the next administration revokes any agreement with the stroke of a pen, as they boast, it will have simply committed a blatant violation of international law.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://en.mfa.ir/index.aspx?siteid=3&fkeyid=&siteid=3&fkeyid=&siteid=3&pageid=1997&newsview=330948|title=Dr. Zarif's Response to the Letter of US Senators|last=Zarif|first=Javad|date=March 9, 2015|publisher=[[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Iran)]]}}</ref>\n\nCotton defended the letter amid criticism that it undermined the president's efforts, \"It's so important we communicated this message straight to Iran... No regrets at all... they already control Tehran, increasingly they control Damascus and Beirut and Baghdad and now Sana'a as well.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2015/03/15/freshmen-gop-sen-cotton-says-no-regrets-about-letter-warning-iran-about-nuclear.html|title=Freshman GOP Senator Cotton says no regrets about letter warning Iran about Nuclear Deterrent|date=March 15, 2015|publisher=[[Fox News]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/videos/march-15-kerry-cotton-manchin/|title=Face the Nation: March 15 Kerry, Cotton, Manchin|date=March 15, 2015|publisher=[[CBS News]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/tom-cotton-us-senator-apparently-does-not-know-the-capital-of-iran-10111640.html|title=Tom Cotton, US Senator, apparently does not know the capital of Iran|last=Guion|first=Payton|date=March 16, 2015|work=[[The Independent]]}}</ref> He continued to defend his action in an interview with [[MSNBC]] by saying, \"There are nothing but hardliners in Iran. They've been killing Americans for 35 years. They kill hundreds of troops in Iraq. Now they control five capitals in the Middle East. There are nothing but hardliners in Tehran and if they do all those things without a nuclear weapon, imagine what they'll do with a nuclear weapon.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.msnbc.com/morning-joe/watch/tom-cotton--i-want-complete-nuclear-disarmament-410915907561|title=Tom Cotton: I want complete nuclear disarmament|date=March 15, 2015|publisher=[[MSNBC]]}}</ref>\n\nCotton received extensive financial support from pro-Israel groups due to his opposition to the Iran nuclear deal and for his hawkish stance toward Iran. Several pro-Israel Republican billionaires who contributed millions of dollars to [[William Kristol]]'s [[Emergency Committee for Israel]] spent $960,000 to support Cotton.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/04/05/us/politics/gops-israel-support-deepens-as-political-contributions-shift.html|title=GOP's Israel support deepens as political contributions shift|last=Lipton|first=Eric|date=April 4, 2015|work=[[The New York Times]]}}{{subscription required}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2018, Cotton introduced the Iran Hostage Taking Accountability Act, a bill that would call for the president to compose a list of Iranians that were \"knowingly responsible for or complicit in...the politically-motivated harassment, abuse, extortion, arrest, trial, conviction, sentencing, or imprisonment\" of Americans and have those on the list face sanctions along with enabling the president to impose sanctions on their family members and bar them from entering the United States Cotton stated that Iran had not changed much since 1981 and called for Americans to avoid Iran and its borders as there were \"many friendly countries in the region that you can visit where you'd be safer.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.arkansasonline.com/news/2018/jul/20/cotton-bill-targets-iran-over-captives-/|title=U.S. Sen. Tom Cotton's bill targets Iran over captives|date=July 20, 2018|first=Frank E.|last=Lockwood|publisher=Arkansas Democrat Gazette}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2019, Cotton said that in the event of a [[Iran\u2013United States relations#2019 escalation in tensions|war with Iran]], the United States could easily win in \"two strikes. The first strike and the last strike.\"<ref name=\":1\" /> He said there would be a \"furious response\" by the United States if there was any provocation from Iran.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n====Russia====\nOn 13 January 2018, in an interview on conservative commentator Hugh Hewitt's radio show, Cotton said that he expects [[Russia]]n officials to \"lie and deny\" about the [[poisoning of Sergei Skripal]], an ex-Russian spy on British soil.<ref name=\"russialiedeny\" >[https://thehill.com/homenews/senate/378177-cotton-russia-will-lie-and-deny-when-confronted-with-british-spy-attack Cotton: Russia will 'lie and deny' about British spy poisoning]. 13 March 2018. ''The Hill''. Retrieved 24 march 2020.</ref> After the [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom]] [[Theresa May]] gave Russia 24 hours to respond to the poison, Cotton said \"I suspect the response will be the typical Russian response. They\u2019ll lie and deny.\"<ref name=\"russialiedeny\" /> Cotton went on to suggest retaliatory measures that the U.K. and the U.S. could implement in response to Russia's alleged actions, including renewed sanctions on oil.<ref name=\"russialiedeny\" />\n\n==Personal life==\nCotton married attorney Anna Peckham in 2014. The couple have two children.<ref>{{cite news|last=Brantley|first=Max|title=Tom Cotton still mum on marriage details|url=https://www.arktimes.com/ArkansasBlog/archives/2014/03/17/tom-cotton-still-mum-on-marriage-details|work=[[Arkansas Times]]|date=March 17, 2014}}</ref> Their first child, a boy, was born on April 27, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mobile.twitter.com/SenTomCotton/status/593178724276768768|title=Hello, world! Since everyone is asking, my name is Gabriel|first=Tom|last=Cotton|publisher=[[Twitter]]|date=April 28, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Gangitano|first=Alex|title=Sen. Tom Cotton Welcomes Second Child|url=http://www.rollcall.com/news/hoh/sen-tom-cotton-welcomes-second-child|work=[[Roll Call]]|date=December 7, 2016}}</ref>\n\nCotton is a member of the [[United Methodist Church]].<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://www.tomcotton.com/2013/08/tom-cotton-announces-u-s-senate-campaign|title=TOM COTTON ANNOUNCES U.S. SENATE CAMPAIGN|publisher=Tom Cotton|date=August 6, 2013}}</ref>\n\nCotton has said that [[Walter Russell Mead]], [[Robert D. Kaplan]], [[Henry Kissinger]], [[Daniel Silva (novelist)|Daniel Silva]], C.J. Vonn, and [[Jason Matthews (novelist)|Jason Matthews]] are among his favorite authors.<ref>{{cite news|last=Takala|first=Rudy|authorlink=Rudy Takala|title=Tom Cotton: 'Deterrence, once lost, is very hard to regain'|url=http://www.washingtonexaminer.com/tom-cotton-deterrence-once-lost-is-very-hard-to-regain/article/2594746=all|work=[[The Washington Examiner]]|date=June 27, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Electoral history==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"5\" |Arkansas's 4th Congressional District Republican Primary Election, 2012\n|-\n|'''Party'''\n|'''Candidate'''\n|'''Votes'''\n|'''%'''\n|'''+%'''\n|-\n|Republican\n|Tom Cotton\n|20,899\n|57.55%\n|\n|-\n|Republican\n|Beth Anne Rankin\n|13,460\n|37.07%\n|\n|-\n|Republican\n|John Cowart\n|1,953\n|5.38%\n|\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"5\" |Arkansas's 4th Congressional District Election, 2012\n|-\n|'''Party'''\n|'''Candidate'''\n|'''Votes'''\n|'''%'''\n|'''+%'''\n|-\n|Republican\n|Tom Cotton\n|154,149\n|59.53%\n|\n|-\n|Democratic\n|Gene Jeffress\n|95,013\n|36.69%\n|\n|-\n|Libertarian\n|Bobby Tullis\n|4,984\n|1.92%\n|\n|-\n|Green\n|Joshua Drake\n|4,807\n|1.86%\n|\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"5\" |U.S. Senate Election in Arkansas, 2014\n|-\n|'''Party'''\n|'''Candidate'''\n|'''Votes'''\n|'''%'''\n|'''+%'''\n|-\n|Republican\n|Tom Cotton\n|478,819\n|56.50%\n|\n|-\n|Democratic\n|Mark Pryor*\n|334,174\n|39.43%\n|\n|-\n|Libertarian\n|Nathan LaFrance\n|17,210\n|2.03%\n|\n|-\n|Green\n|Mark Swaney\n|16,797\n|1.98%\n|\n|-\n|Write-in votes\n|Write-in votes\n|505\n|0.06%\n|\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of people from Arkansas]]\n* [[List of United States Representatives from Arkansas]]\n* [[List of United States Senators from Arkansas]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n<!--\n  ===============================================================================\n   WIKIPEDIA IS NOT A COLLECTION OF LINKS. Only a limited number of new links \n   should be added to this article. PLEASE DO NOT ADD external links to sites with\n   information already in the article or in its sources.\n\n   See [[Wikipedia:External links]] and [[Wikipedia:Spam]] for further details\n  ===============================================================================\n-->\n* {{official website|http://cotton.senate.gov/}}\n* {{C-SPAN|Thomas Cotton}}\n* {{CongLinks|congbio=C001095|votesmart=135651|fec=S4AR00103|congress=tom-cotton/2098}}\n* {{Ballotpedia|Tom_Cotton|Tom Cotton}}\n* {{Curlie|Regional/North_America/United_States/Arkansas/Government/Federal/US_Senate/Tom_Cotton_%5BR%5D|Tom Cotton}}\n<!-- EDITORS NOTE: Please follow the [[WP:EL]] guideline where possible and consider discussing on the talk page. Thank you. -->\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{US House succession box\n|state    = Arkansas\n|district = 4\n|before   = [[Mike Ross (politician)|Mike Ross]] \n|after    = [[Bruce Westerman]]\n|years    = 2013\u20132015}}\n|-\n{{s-ppo}}\n|-\n{{s-vac|last=[[Tim Hutchinson]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title={{nowrap|[[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] nominee for [[List of United States Senators from Arkansas|U.S. Senator]] from [[Arkansas]]}}<br />([[Classes of United States Senators|Class 2]])|years=[[United States Senate election in Arkansas, 2014|2014]]<!-- , [[2020 United States Senate election in Arkansas|2020]] -->}}\n{{s-inc|recent}}\n|-\n{{s-par|us-sen}}\n{{U.S. Senator box\n|state     = Arkansas\n|class     = 2\n|before    = [[Mark Pryor]]\n|start     = 2015\n|alongside = [[John Boozman]]}}\n|-\n{{s-hon}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Chris Murphy]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of youngest members of the United States Congress|Baby of the Senate]]|years=2015\u20132019}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Josh Hawley]]}}\n|-\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[James Lankford]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Seniority in the United States Senate|United States Senators by seniority]]|years=74th}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Steve Daines]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{USCongRep-start|congresses=113th\u2013present [[United States Congress]]es|state=[[Arkansas]]}}\n{{USCongRep/AR/113}}\n{{USCongRep/AR/114}}\n{{USCongRep/AR/115}}\n{{USCongRep/AR/116}}\n{{USCongRep-end}}\n{{AR-FedRep}}\n{{Current U.S. Senators}}\n{{Current Arkansas statewide political officials}}\n{{Subject bar|portal1=Biography|portal2=Conservatism|portal3=Politics|portal4=