{"title_page": "Smoky Burgess", "text_new": "{{Infobox baseball biography\n|name=Smoky Burgess\n|image=Smoky Burgess 1953.jpg\n|caption=Burgess in about 1953.\n|position=[[Catcher]]\n|birth_date={{Birth date|1927|2|6}}\n|birth_place=[[Caroleen, North Carolina]]\n|death_date={{death date and age|1991|9|15|1927|2|6}}\n|death_place=[[Rutherfordton, North Carolina]]\n|bats=Left\n|throws=Right\n|debutleague = MLB\n|debutdate=April 19\n|debutyear=1949\n|debutteam=Chicago Cubs\n|finalleague = MLB\n|finaldate=October 1\n|finalyear=1967\n|finalteam=Chicago White Sox\n|statleague = MLB\n|stat1label=[[Batting average (baseball)|Batting average]]\n|stat1value=.295\n|stat2label=[[Home run]]s\n|stat2value=126\n|stat3label=[[Runs batted in]]\n|stat3value=673\n|teams=\n* [[Chicago Cubs]] ({{mlby|1949}}, {{mlby|1951}})\n* [[Philadelphia Phillies]] ({{mlby|1952}}\u2013{{mlby|1955}})\n* [[Cincinnati Reds]] ({{mlby|1955}}\u2013{{mlby|1958}})\n* [[Pittsburgh Pirates]] ({{mlby|1959}}\u2013{{mlby|1964}})\n* [[Chicago White Sox]] ({{mlby|1964}}\u2013{{mlby|1967}})\n|highlights=\n* 9\u00d7 [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star]] ([[1954 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|1954]], [[1955 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|1955]], [[1959 Major League Baseball All-Star Game (first game)|1959]]\u2013[[1961 Major League Baseball All-Star Game (second game)|1961\u00b2]], [[1964 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|1964]])\n* [[World Series]] champion ({{wsy|1960}})\n* [[Cincinnati Reds Hall of Fame and Museum|Cincinnati Reds Hall of Fame]]\n}}\n'''Forrest Harrill \"Smoky\" Burgess''' (February 6, 1927 \u2013 September 15, 1991),<ref name=\"Smoky Burgess obituary at the New York Times\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1991/09/17/obituaries/forrest-smoky-burgess-baseball-player-64.html|title=Forrest (Smoky) Burgess; Baseball Player, 64|first=The Associated|last=Press|publisher=}}</ref> was an [[Americans|American]] [[professional baseball]] [[catcher]] / [[pinch hitter]], [[Coach (baseball)|coach]], and [[Scout (sports)#Kinds of scouts|scout]], who played in [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB) from {{by|1949}} to {{by|1967}}. A nine-time [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star]], Burgess became known, later in his career, for his abilities as an elite pinch hitter, setting the MLB career record for career pinch-hits with 145.<ref name=\"George Vass, Baseball Digest\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=vy0DAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA30&lpg=PA30&dq=the+toughest+job+in+baseball&source=bl&ots=10ka7j1rK9&sig=b-67RBVr4RHhTrtutioUjvvLgZI&hl=en&ei=voXESpuZDJT24Aaut7g0&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=3&ved=0CBAQ6AEwAjgK&safe=active#v=onepage&q=the%20toughest%20job%20in%20baseball&f=false George Vass], Baseball Digest, November 2004, Vol. 63, No. 11, {{ISSN|0005-609X}}</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=4zADAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA37&lpg=PA37&dq=Red+Schoendienst+single+season+pinch+hit+record&source=bl&ots=Jr73Pb26Q1&sig=t2CF8KtX_bYf1LH9eCfmtvpv1xI&hl=en&ei=A6nFSqRlyKD-BtLDwJYI&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=4&safe=active#v=onepage&q=Red%20Schoendienst%20single%20season%20pinch%20hit%20record&f=false Jerry Beach], Baseball Digest, June 1999, Vol. 58, No. 6, {{ISSN|0005-609X}}</ref> During his playing days, he stood {{convert|5|ft|8|in|m}} tall, weighing {{convert|188|lb|kg}}. Burgess batted [[left-handed]] and threw [[right-handed]].<ref name=\"Smoky Burgess at Baseball Reference\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/b/burgesm01.shtml|title=Smoky Burgess Stats|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=[[baseball-reference.com]]}}</ref>\n\n== Baseball career ==\nBorn in [[Caroleen, North Carolina|Caroleen]], [[North Carolina]], Burgess was signed as an amateur [[free agent]] by the [[Chicago Cubs]] in [[1944 Chicago Cubs season|1944]].<ref name=\"Smoky Burgess Trades and Transactions at Baseball Almanac\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-almanac.com/players/trades.php?p=burgesm01|title=Smoky Burgess Trades and Transactions by Baseball Almanac|first=Baseball Almanac|last=Inc.|website=www.baseball-almanac.com}}</ref> In {{by|1947}}, he led the [[Tri-State League]] with a .387 [[batting average (baseball)|batting average]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/register/leader.cgi?type=bat&id=c4c293a2|title=1947 Tri-State League Batting Leaders - Baseball-Reference|work=[[baseball-reference.com]]|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|accessdate=April 16, 2019}}</ref> Burgess followed that by leading (minimum 100 games played) the [[Southern Association]] with a .386 average, in {{by|1948}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/register/leader.cgi?type=bat&id=05dd902d|title=1948 Southern Association Batting Leaders - Baseball-Reference|work=[[baseball-reference.com]]|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|accessdate=April 16, 2019}}</ref> He made his major league debut at the age of 22 with the Chicago Cubs on April 19, [[1949 Chicago Cubs season|1949]].<ref name=\"Smoky Burgess at Baseball Reference\"/> In October [[1951 Chicago Cubs season|1951]], Burgess was traded to the [[Cincinnati Reds]], who promptly traded him to the [[Philadelphia Phillies]] for catcher [[Andy Seminick]] before the start of the [[1952 Philadelphia Phillies season|1952]] season.<ref name=\"Smoky Burgess Trades and Transactions at Baseball Almanac\"/> With the Phillies, he [[Platoon system|platooned]] alongside the right-handed-hitting [[Stan Lopata]].<ref name=\"Catcher With The Highest Average\">{{cite magazine|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zTIDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA59&dq=smoky+Burgess+baseball+digest&cd=2#v=onepage&q=smoky%20Burgess%20baseball%20digest&f=false|title=Catcher With The Highest Average |author=Ed Rumill |magazine=Baseball Digest |date=December 1963 |volume=10 |issn=0005-609X|publisher=}}</ref> Burgess had his best season in [[1954 Philadelphia Phillies season|1954]], when he had a .368 batting average in 108 games for the Phillies, earning his first [[1954 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star Game]] selection.<ref name=\"Smoky Burgess at Baseball Reference\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/ALS/ALS195407130.shtml|title=1954 All-Star Game Box Score, July 13 - Baseball-Reference.com|website=Baseball-Reference.com}}</ref>\n\nAt the beginning of the [[1955 Cincinnati Reds season|1955]] season, Burgess was once again traded for Andy Seminick and returned to Cincinnati, where he finally got the chance to play every day.<ref name=\"Smoky Burgess Trades and Transactions at Baseball Almanac\"/><ref name=\"Catcher With The Highest Average\"/> He rose to the occasion, hitting for a .306 [[batting average (baseball)|batting average]] for the rest of the season along with 20 [[home run]]s and 77 [[runs batted in]], gaining his second consecutive berth on the National League [[1955 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star]] team.<ref name=\"Smoky Burgess at Baseball Reference\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/NLS/NLS195507120.shtml|title=1955 All-Star Game Box Score, July 12 - Baseball-Reference.com|website=Baseball-Reference.com}}</ref> On July 29, [[1955 Cincinnati Reds season|1955]], Burgess hit three home runs and had nine runs batted in during a game against the [[Pittsburgh Pirates]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/CIN/CIN195507290.shtml|title=Pittsburgh Pirates at Cincinnati Redlegs Box Score, July 29, 1955 - Baseball-Reference.com|website=Baseball-Reference.com}}</ref> He began the [[1956 Cincinnati Reds season|1956]] season as the Reds' starting catcher, but when the team faltered early in the season, Reds [[Manager (baseball)|manager]] [[Birdie Tebbetts]] decided to shake things up, and replaced Burgess with a younger man, [[Ed Bailey]].<ref name=\"Bailey- Next Catching Great?\">{{cite magazine|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TSwDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA49&dq=ed+bailey+baseball+digest&hl=en&ei=9YAUTPiTE4GKlwfXxpXADA&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CCgQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=ed%20bailey%20baseball%20digest&f=false|title=Bailey- Next Catching Great? |author=Bob Pile |magazine=Baseball Digest |date=August 1956 |volume=15 |number=7 |issn=0005-609X|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn [[1959 Pittsburgh Pirates season|1959]], Burgess was traded along with [[Harvey Haddix]] and [[Don Hoak]] to the Pittsburgh Pirates for [[Whammy Douglas]], [[Jim Pendleton]] and [[John Powers (baseball)|John Powers]].<ref name=\"Smoky Burgess Trades and Transactions at Baseball Almanac\"/> He was the Pirates catcher on May 26, [[1959 in baseball|1959]] when [[Harvey Haddix's near-perfect game|Haddix took a perfect game into the 13th inning]] against the [[1957 Milwaukee Braves season|Milwaukee Braves]], before losing the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/MLN/MLN195905260.shtml|title=Pittsburgh Pirates at Milwaukee Braves Box Score, May 26, 1959 - Baseball-Reference.com|website=Baseball-Reference.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-almanac.com/boxscore/05261959.shtml|title=Harvey Haddix Perfect Game Box Score by Baseball Almanac|website=www.baseball-almanac.com}}</ref> Burgess also won a [[1960 World Series|World Series]] with the Pirates in [[1960 Pittsburgh Pirates season|1960]], batting .333 in the seven-game series.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/postseason/1960_WS.shtml|title=1960 World Series - Pittsburgh Pirates over New York Yankees (4-3) - Baseball-Reference.com|website=Baseball-Reference.com}}</ref><ref name=\"Smoky Burgess at Baseball Reference\"/>\n\nBy [[1963 Pittsburgh Pirates season|1963]], [[Jim Pagliaroni]] had taken over as the Pirates' starting catcher and in late [[1964 Pittsburgh Pirates season|1964]], Burgess was acquired by the [[Chicago White Sox]], who were in the middle of a heated [[Pennant (sports)|pennant]] race.<ref name=\"Smoky Burgess Trades and Transactions at Baseball Almanac\"/> In his first plate appearance with the White Sox, on September 15, against the [[1964 Detroit Tigers season|Detroit Tigers]], he hit a game-tying home run off pitcher [[Dave Wickersham]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/DET/DET196409150.shtml|title=Chicago White Sox at Detroit Tigers Box Score, September 15, 1964 - Baseball-Reference.com|website=Baseball-Reference.com}}</ref> Over the next three years, Burgess was used almost exclusively as a pinch hitter, appearing in just 7 games behind the [[Home plate|plate]].<ref name=\"Smoky Burgess at  Baseball Reference\"/> In {{by|1966}}, he set a Major League record which still stands for the most games in a season (79) by a non-pitcher who did not score a run.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Preston|first1=JG|title=Nobody drove them in: the unusual seasons of Ron Northey, Bob Nieman and Smoky Burgess|url=https://prestonjg.wordpress.com/2015/03/30/nobody-drove-them-in-the-unusual-seasons-of-ron-northey-bob-nieman-and-smoky-burgess/|website=prestonjg.wordpress.com|accessdate=4 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nBurgess played his final major league game on October 1, [[1967 Chicago White Sox season|1967]] at the age of 40.<ref name=\"Smoky Burgess at Baseball Reference\"/>\n\n== Career statistics ==\nDuring an eighteen-year major league career, Burgess played in 1,691 [[Games played|games]], hitting for a .295 career [[batting average (baseball)|batting average]], with 126 [[home run]]s, 673 [[Runs batted in|RBI]], and a .362 [[on-base percentage]]. He accumulated 1,318 career [[hit (baseball)|hits]], with 230 [[double (baseball)|doubles]], and 33 [[triple (baseball)|triples]].<ref name=\"Smoky Burgess at Baseball Reference\"/> His .295 career batting average ranked him 10th among Major League catchers, as of 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://members.tripod.com/bb_catchers/catchers/careerld.htm|title=Encyclopedia of Baseball Catchers Career Batting Leaders|website=members.tripod.com|accessdate=April 16, 2019}}</ref> A six-time [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star]], Burgess led [[National League]] (NL) catchers in [[fielding percentage]] three times, in [[1953 Philadelphia Phillies season|1953]], [[1960 Pittsburgh Pirates season|1960]], and [[1961 Pittsburgh Pirates season|1961]].<ref name=\"Smoky Burgess at Baseball Reference\"/> His Major League record of 145 career pinch hits was broken by [[Manny Mota]], in {{by|1979}}. Along with [[Curt Simmons]], he was the last player to formally retire, who had played in the major leagues in the 1940s (not counting [[Minnie Mi\u00f1oso]], who un-retired twice).\n\n== Post-playing career==\nWhen his playing career ended, Burgess spent many years with the [[Atlanta Braves]] as a scout and [[Minor League Baseball|minor league]] [[Coach (baseball)#Offensive coaches: hitting coach and base coaches|batting coach]] with the [[Pulaski Braves]], in [[Pulaski, VA]]. \n\nBurgess was inducted into the [[Cincinnati Reds Hall of Fame]], in 1975.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cincinnati.reds.mlb.com/cin/ballpark/museum/hofers.jsp|title=Hall of Fame & Museum - Reds Hall of Famers|website=Cincinnati Reds}}</ref> \n\nBurgess was inducted into the [[North Carolina Sports Hall of Fame]], in 1978.<ref>[http://www.ncshof.org/inductees_detail.php?i_recid=2 Smoky Burgess at the North Carolina Sports Hall of Fame] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101127054008/http://ncshof.org/inductees_detail.php?i_recid=2 |date=2010-11-27 }}</ref> \n\nBurgess died at age 64, in [[Rutherfordton, North Carolina]], September 15, 1991.<ref name=\"Smoky Burgess obituary at the New York Times\"/>\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[Pinch hitter#MLB all-time pinch hit leaders|Major League Baseball all-time pinch hit leaders]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{baseballstats|mlb=111705|espn=19716|br=b/burgesm01|fangraphs=1001665|brm=burges001for|retro=B/Pburgs101}}\n*[https://sabr.org/bioproj/person/24804821 Smoky Burgess] at SABR (Baseball BioProject)\n*[https://www.thedeadballera.com/Obits/Obits_B/Burgess.Smokey.Obit.html Smoky Burgess] at The Deadball Era\n*{{findagrave|6182147}}\n* [https://www.nytimes.com/1991/09/17/obituaries/forrest-smoky-burgess-baseball-player-64.html Smoky Burgess obituary at the ''New York Times'']\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=My4DAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA41&dq=smoky+Burgess+baseball+digest&cd=3#v=onepage&q=smoky%20Burgess%20baseball%20digest&f=false \"Catcher With A Belly\", by Frank Yeutter, ''Baseball Digest'', May 1953]\n* [https://archive.org/details/Sports-Illustrated-1959-06-22/page/n51 \"Let Me Have Men About Me That Are Fat...\", by Walter Bingham, ''Sports Illustrated'', June 22, 1959]\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=zTIDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA59&dq=smoky+Burgess+baseball+digest&cd=2#v=onepage&q=smoky%20Burgess%20baseball%20digest&f=false \"Catcher With The Highest Average\", by Ed Rumill, ''Baseball Digest'', December 1963]\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=XDIDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA65&dq=smoky+Burgess+baseball+digest&cd=1#v=onepage&q=smoky%20Burgess%20baseball%20digest&f=false \"The Buddha with the Clutch Touch\", by Francis Stan, ''Baseball Digest'', July 1966]\n\n{{1960 Pittsburgh Pirates}}\n{{Cincinnati Reds Hall of Fame}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Burgess, Smoky}}\n\n[[Category:1927 births]]\n[[Category:1991 deaths]]\n[[Category:Baseball players from North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball catchers]]\n[[Category:National League All-Stars]]\n[[Category:Chicago Cubs players]]\n[[Category:Chicago White Sox players]]\n[[Category:Cincinnati Reds players]]\n[[Category:Philadelphia Phillies players]]\n[[Category:Pittsburgh Pirates players]]\n[[Category:Atlanta Braves scouts]]\n[[Category:Minor league baseball coaches]]\n[[Category:Lockport Cubs players]]\n[[Category:Portsmouth Cubs players]]\n[[Category:Los Angeles Angels (minor league) players]]\n[[Category:Fayetteville Cubs players]]\n[[Category:Macon Peaches players]]\n[[Category:Nashville Vols players]]\n[[Category:Springfield Cubs players]]\n[[Category:Baseball coaches from North Carolina]]\n[[Category:People from Caroleen, North Carolina]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox baseball biography\n|name=Smoky Burgess\n|image=Smoky Burgess 1953.jpg\n|caption=Burgess in about 1953.\n|position=[[Catcher]]\n|bats=Left\n|throws=Right\n|birth_date={{Birth date|1927|2|6}}\n|birth_place=[[Caroleen, North Carolina]]\n|death_date={{death date and age|1991|9|15|1927|2|6}}\n|death_place=[[Rutherfordton, North Carolina]]\n|debutleague = MLB\n|debutdate=April 19\n|debutyear=1949\n|debutteam=Chicago Cubs\n|finalleague = MLB\n|finaldate=October 1\n|finalyear=1967\n|finalteam=Chicago White Sox\n|statleague = MLB\n|stat1label=[[Batting average (baseball)|Batting average]]\n|stat1value=.295\n|stat2label=[[Home run]]s\n|stat2value=126\n|stat3label=[[Run batted in|Runs batted in]]\n|stat3value=673\n|teams=\n* [[Chicago Cubs]] ({{mlby|1949}}, {{mlby|1951}})\n* [[Philadelphia Phillies]] ({{mlby|1952}}\u2013{{mlby|1955}})\n* [[Cincinnati Reds]] ({{mlby|1955}}\u2013{{mlby|1958}})\n* [[Pittsburgh Pirates]] ({{mlby|1959}}\u2013{{mlby|1964}})\n* [[Chicago White Sox]] ({{mlby|1964}}\u2013{{mlby|1967}})\n|highlights=\n* 9\u00d7 [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star]] ([[1954 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|1954]], [[1955 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|1955]], [[1959 Major League Baseball All-Star Game (first game)|1959]]\u2013[[1961 Major League Baseball All-Star Game (second game)|1961\u00b2]], [[1964 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|1964]])\n* [[World Series]] champion ({{wsy|1960}})\n* [[Cincinnati Reds Hall of Fame and Museum|Cincinnati Reds Hall of Fame]]\n}}\n'''Forrest Harrill \"Smoky\" Burgess''' (February 6, 1927 \u2013 September 15, 1991),<ref name=\"Smoky Burgess obituary at the New York Times\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1991/09/17/obituaries/forrest-smoky-burgess-baseball-player-64.html|title=Forrest (Smoky) Burgess; Baseball Player, 64|first=The Associated|last=Press|publisher=}}</ref> was an [[Americans|American]] [[professional baseball]] [[catcher]] / [[pinch hitter]], [[Coach (baseball)|coach]], and [[Scout (sports)#Kinds of scouts|scout]], who played in [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB) from {{by|1949}} to {{by|1967}}. A nine-time [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star]], Burgess became known, later in his career, for his abilities as an elite pinch hitter, setting the MLB career record for career pinch-hits with 145.<ref name=\"George Vass, Baseball Digest\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=vy0DAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA30&lpg=PA30&dq=the+toughest+job+in+baseball&source=bl&ots=10ka7j1rK9&sig=b-67RBVr4RHhTrtutioUjvvLgZI&hl=en&ei=voXESpuZDJT24Aaut7g0&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=3&ved=0CBAQ6AEwAjgK&safe=active#v=onepage&q=the%20toughest%20job%20in%20baseball&f=false George Vass], Baseball Digest, November 2004, Vol. 63, No. 11, {{ISSN|0005-609X}}</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=4zADAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA37&lpg=PA37&dq=Red+Schoendienst+single+season+pinch+hit+record&source=bl&ots=Jr73Pb26Q1&sig=t2CF8KtX_bYf1LH9eCfmtvpv1xI&hl=en&ei=A6nFSqRlyKD-BtLDwJYI&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=4&safe=active#v=onepage&q=Red%20Schoendienst%20single%20season%20pinch%20hit%20record&f=false Jerry Beach], Baseball Digest, June 1999, Vol. 58, No. 6, {{ISSN|0005-609X}}</ref> During his playing days, he stood {{convert|5|ft|8|in|m}} tall, weighing {{convert|188|lb|kg}}. Burgess batted [[left-handed]] and threw [[right-handed]].<ref name=\"Smoky Burgess at Baseball Reference\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/b/burgesm01.shtml|title=Smoky Burgess Stats|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=[[baseball-reference.com]]}}</ref>\n\n== Baseball career ==\nBorn in [[Caroleen, North Carolina|Caroleen]], [[North Carolina]], Burgess was signed as an amateur [[free agent]] by the [[Chicago Cubs]] in [[1944 Chicago Cubs season|1944]].<ref name=\"Smoky Burgess Trades and Transactions at Baseball Almanac\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-almanac.com/players/trades.php?p=burgesm01|title=Smoky Burgess Trades and Transactions by Baseball Almanac|first=Baseball Almanac|last=Inc.|website=www.baseball-almanac.com}}</ref> In {{by|1947}}, he led the [[Tri-State League]] with a .387 [[batting average (baseball)|batting average]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/register/leader.cgi?type=bat&id=c4c293a2|title=1947 Tri-State League Batting Leaders - Baseball-Reference|work=[[baseball-reference.com]]|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|accessdate=April 16, 2019}}</ref> Burgess followed that by leading (minimum 100 games played) the [[Southern Association]] with a .386 average, in {{by|1948}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/register/leader.cgi?type=bat&id=05dd902d|title=1948 Southern Association Batting Leaders - Baseball-Reference|work=[[baseball-reference.com]]|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|accessdate=April 16, 2019}}</ref> He made his major league debut at the age of 22 with the Chicago Cubs on April 19, [[1949 Chicago Cubs season|1949]].<ref name=\"Smoky Burgess at Baseball Reference\"/> In October [[1951 Chicago Cubs season|1951]], Burgess was traded to the [[Cincinnati Reds]], who promptly traded him to the [[Philadelphia Phillies]] for catcher [[Andy Seminick]] before the start of the [[1952 Philadelphia Phillies season|1952]] season.<ref name=\"Smoky Burgess Trades and Transactions at Baseball Almanac\"/> With the Phillies, he [[Platoon system|platooned]] alongside the right-handed-hitting [[Stan Lopata]].<ref name=\"Catcher With The Highest Average\">{{cite magazine|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zTIDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA59&dq=smoky+Burgess+baseball+digest&cd=2#v=onepage&q=smoky%20Burgess%20baseball%20digest&f=false|title=Catcher With The Highest Average |author=Ed Rumill |magazine=Baseball Digest |date=December 1963 |volume=10 |issn=0005-609X|publisher=}}</ref> Burgess had his best season in [[1954 Philadelphia Phillies season|1954]], when he had a .368 batting average in 108 games for the Phillies, earning his first [[1954 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star Game]] selection.<ref name=\"Smoky Burgess at Baseball Reference\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/ALS/ALS195407130.shtml|title=1954 All-Star Game Box Score, July 13 - Baseball-Reference.com|website=Baseball-Reference.com}}</ref>\n\nAt the beginning of the [[1955 Cincinnati Reds season|1955]] season, Burgess was once again traded for Andy Seminick and returned to Cincinnati, where he finally got the chance to play every day.<ref name=\"Smoky Burgess Trades and Transactions at Baseball Almanac\"/><ref name=\"Catcher With The Highest Average\"/> He rose to the occasion, hitting for a .306 [[batting average (baseball)|batting average]] for the rest of the season along with 20 [[home run]]s and 77 [[runs batted in]], gaining his second consecutive berth on the National League [[1955 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star]] team.<ref name=\"Smoky Burgess at Baseball Reference\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/NLS/NLS195507120.shtml|title=1955 All-Star Game Box Score, July 12 - Baseball-Reference.com|website=Baseball-Reference.com}}</ref> On July 29, [[1955 Cincinnati Reds season|1955]], Burgess hit three home runs and had nine runs batted in during a game against the [[Pittsburgh Pirates]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/CIN/CIN195507290.shtml|title=Pittsburgh Pirates at Cincinnati Redlegs Box Score, July 29, 1955 - Baseball-Reference.com|website=Baseball-Reference.com}}</ref> He began the [[1956 Cincinnati Reds season|1956]] season as the Reds' starting catcher, but when the team faltered early in the season, Reds [[Manager (baseball)|manager]] [[Birdie Tebbetts]] decided to shake things up, and replaced Burgess with a younger man, [[Ed Bailey]].<ref name=\"Bailey- Next Catching Great?\">{{cite magazine|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TSwDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA49&dq=ed+bailey+baseball+digest&hl=en&ei=9YAUTPiTE4GKlwfXxpXADA&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CCgQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=ed%20bailey%20baseball%20digest&f=false|title=Bailey- Next Catching Great? |author=Bob Pile |magazine=Baseball Digest |date=August 1956 |volume=15 |number=7 |issn=0005-609X|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn [[1959 Pittsburgh Pirates season|1959]], Burgess was traded along with [[Harvey Haddix]] and [[Don Hoak]] to the Pittsburgh Pirates for [[Whammy Douglas]], [[Jim Pendleton]] and [[John Powers (baseball)|John Powers]].<ref name=\"Smoky Burgess Trades and Transactions at Baseball Almanac\"/> He was the Pirates catcher on May 26, [[1959 in baseball|1959]] when [[Harvey Haddix's near-perfect game|Haddix took a perfect game into the 13th inning]] against the [[1957 Milwaukee Braves season|Milwaukee Braves]], before losing the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/MLN/MLN195905260.shtml|title=Pittsburgh Pirates at Milwaukee Braves Box Score, May 26, 1959 - Baseball-Reference.com|website=Baseball-Reference.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-almanac.com/boxscore/05261959.shtml|title=Harvey Haddix Perfect Game Box Score by Baseball Almanac|website=www.baseball-almanac.com}}</ref> Burgess also won a [[1960 World Series|World Series]] with the Pirates in [[1960 Pittsburgh Pirates season|1960]], batting .333 in the seven-game series.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/postseason/1960_WS.shtml|title=1960 World Series - Pittsburgh Pirates over New York Yankees (4-3) - Baseball-Reference.com|website=Baseball-Reference.com}}</ref><ref name=\"Smoky Burgess at Baseball Reference\"/>\n\nBy [[1963 Pittsburgh Pirates season|1963]], [[Jim Pagliaroni]] had taken over as the Pirates' starting catcher and in late [[1964 Pittsburgh Pirates season|1964]], Burgess was acquired by the [[Chicago White Sox]], who were in the middle of a heated [[Pennant (sports)|pennant]] race.<ref name=\"Smoky Burgess Trades and Transactions at Baseball Almanac\"/> In his first plate appearance with the White Sox, on September 15, against the [[1964 Detroit Tigers season|Detroit Tigers]], he hit a game-tying home run off pitcher [[Dave Wickersham]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/DET/DET196409150.shtml|title=Chicago White Sox at Detroit Tigers Box Score, September 15, 1964 - Baseball-Reference.com|website=Baseball-Reference.com}}</ref> Over the next three years, Burgess was used almost exclusively as a pinch hitter, appearing in just 7 games behind the [[Home plate|plate]].<ref name=\"Smoky Burgess at  Baseball Reference\"/> In {{by|1966}}, he set a Major League record which still stands for the most games in a season (79) by a non-pitcher who did not score a run.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Preston|first1=JG|title=Nobody drove them in: the unusual seasons of Ron Northey, Bob Nieman and Smoky Burgess|url=https://prestonjg.wordpress.com/2015/03/30/nobody-drove-them-in-the-unusual-seasons-of-ron-northey-bob-nieman-and-smoky-burgess/|website=prestonjg.wordpress.com|accessdate=4 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nBurgess played his final major league game on October 1, [[1967 Chicago White Sox season|1967]] at the age of 40.<ref name=\"Smoky Burgess at Baseball Reference\"/>\n\n== Career statistics ==\nDuring an eighteen-year major league career, Burgess played in 1,691 [[Games played|games]], hitting for a .295 career [[batting average (baseball)|batting average]], with 126 [[home run]]s, 673 [[Runs batted in|RBI]], and a .362 [[on-base percentage]]. He accumulated 1,318 career [[hit (baseball)|hits]], with 230 [[double (baseball)|doubles]], and 33 [[triple (baseball)|triples]].<ref name=\"Smoky Burgess at Baseball Reference\"/> His .295 career batting average ranked him 10th among Major League catchers, as of 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://members.tripod.com/bb_catchers/catchers/careerld.htm|title=Encyclopedia of Baseball Catchers Career Batting Leaders|website=members.tripod.com|accessdate=April 16, 2019}}</ref> A six-time [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star]], Burgess led [[National League]] (NL) catchers in [[fielding percentage]] three times, in [[1953 Philadelphia Phillies season|1953]], [[1960 Pittsburgh Pirates season|1960]], and [[1961 Pittsburgh Pirates season|1961]].<ref name=\"Smoky Burgess at Baseball Reference\"/> His Major League record of 145 career pinch hits was broken by [[Manny Mota]], in {{by|1979}}. Along with [[Curt Simmons]], he was the last player to formally retire, who had played in the major leagues in the 1940s (not counting [[Minnie Mi\u00f1oso]], who un-retired twice).\n\n== Post-playing career==\nWhen his playing career ended, Burgess spent many years with the [[Atlanta Braves]] as a scout and [[Minor League Baseball|minor league]] [[Coach (baseball)#Offensive coaches: hitting coach and base coaches|batting coach]] with the [[Pulaski Braves]], in [[Pulaski, VA]]. \n\nBurgess was inducted into the [[Cincinnati Reds Hall of Fame]], in 1975.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cincinnati.reds.mlb.com/cin/ballpark/museum/hofers.jsp|title=Hall of Fame & Museum - Reds Hall of Famers|website=Cincinnati Reds}}</ref> \n\nBurgess was inducted into the [[North Carolina Sports Hall of Fame]], in 1978.<ref>[http://www.ncshof.org/inductees_detail.php?i_recid=2 Smoky Burgess at the North Carolina Sports Hall of Fame] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101127054008/http://ncshof.org/inductees_detail.php?i_recid=2 |date=2010-11-27 }}</ref> \n\nBurgess died at age 64, in [[Rutherfordton, North Carolina]], September 15, 1991.<ref name=\"Smoky Burgess obituary at the New York Times\"/>\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[Pinch hitter#MLB all-time pinch hit leaders|Major League Baseball all-time pinch hit leaders]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{baseballstats|mlb=111705|espn=19716|br=b/burgesm01|fangraphs=1001665|brm=burges001for|retro=B/Pburgs101}}\n*[https://sabr.org/bioproj/person/24804821 Smoky Burgess] at SABR (Baseball BioProject)\n*[https://www.thedeadballera.com/Obits/Obits_B/Burgess.Smokey.Obit.html Smoky Burgess] at The Deadball Era\n*{{findagrave|6182147}}\n* [https://www.nytimes.com/1991/09/17/obituaries/forrest-smoky-burgess-baseball-player-64.html Smoky Burgess obituary at the ''New York Times'']\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=My4DAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA41&dq=smoky+Burgess+baseball+digest&cd=3#v=onepage&q=smoky%20Burgess%20baseball%20digest&f=false \"Catcher With A Belly\", by Frank Yeutter, ''Baseball Digest'', May 1953]\n* [https://archive.org/details/Sports-Illustrated-1959-06-22/page/n51 \"Let Me Have Men About Me That Are Fat...\", by Walter Bingham, ''Sports Illustrated'', June 22, 1959]\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=zTIDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA59&dq=smoky+Burgess+baseball+digest&cd=2#v=onepage&q=smoky%20Burgess%20baseball%20digest&f=false \"Catcher With The Highest Average\", by Ed Rumill, ''Baseball Digest'', December 1963]\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=XDIDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA65&dq=smoky+Burgess+baseball+digest&cd=1#v=onepage&q=smoky%20Burgess%20baseball%20digest&f=false \"The Buddha with the Clutch Touch\", by Francis Stan, ''Baseball Digest'', July 1966]\n\n{{1960 Pittsburgh Pirates}}\n{{Cincinnati Reds Hall of Fame}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Burgess, Smoky}}\n\n[[Category:1927 births]]\n[[Category:1991 deaths]]\n[[Category:Baseball players from North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball catchers]]\n[[Category:National League All-Stars]]\n[[Category:Chicago Cubs players]]\n[[Category:Chicago White Sox players]]\n[[Category:Cincinnati Reds players]]\n[[Category:Philadelphia Phillies players]]\n[[Category:Pittsburgh Pirates players]]\n[[Category:Atlanta Braves scouts]]\n[[Category:Minor league baseball coaches]]\n[[Category:Lockport Cubs players]]\n[[Category:Portsmouth Cubs players]]\n[[Category:Los Angeles Angels (minor league) players]]\n[[Category:Fayetteville Cubs players]]\n[[Category:Macon Peaches players]]\n[[Category:Nashville Vols players]]\n[[Category:Springfield Cubs players]]\n[[Category:Baseball coaches from North Carolina]]\n[[Category:People from Caroleen, North Carolina]]\n", "name_user": "98.200.13.215", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Smoky_Burgess"}
{"title_page": "Yining", "text_new": "{{About|the city|the adjacent county|Yining County|other uses}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n<!-- See Template:Infobox settlement for additional fields and descriptions -->\n| name                            = Yining\n| official_name                   = Yining City\n| native_name                     = {{native name|zh|\u4f0a\u5b81\u5e02}}<br/>{{native name|ug|\u063a\u06c7\u0644\u062c\u0627 \u0634\u06d5\u06be\u0649\u0631\u0649}}<br/>{{native name|kk|\u0642\u06c7\u0644\u062c\u0627 \u0642\u0627\u0644\u0627\u0633\u0649}}\n| other_name                      = Kuldja; Ining\n| settlement_type                 = [[County-level city]]\n| pushpin_map                     = Xinjiang\n| pushpin_label_position          = \n| pushpin_map_caption             = Location in Xinjiang\n| pushpin_mapsize                 = \n| coordinates                     = {{coord|43|55|N|81|19|E|region:CN-65|display=inline,title}}\n| image_skyline                   = \u82cf\u78a7\u6021\u5546\u53a6 - panoramio.jpg\n| imagesize                       = \n| image_alt                       = \n| image_caption                   = Cityscape of Yining\n| image_map                       = \n| mapsize                         = \n| map_alt                         = \n| map_caption                     = \n| image_map1                      = \n| mapsize1                        = \n| map_alt1                        = \n| map_caption1                    = \n| image_dot_map                   = \n| dot_mapsize                     = \n| dot_map_base_alt                = \n| dot_map_alt                     = \n| dot_map_caption                 = \n| dot_x                           = \n| dot_y                           = \n| coor_pinpoint                   = \n| coordinates_footnotes           = \n| subdivision_type                = Country\n| subdivision_name                = People's Republic of China\n| subdivision_type1               = [[Autonomous regions of China|Region]]\n| subdivi